ates on August 14, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/P-Bio-Season-One/dp/B07DXDMDYX/ref=tmm_dvd_title_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=|title=Amazon.com: A.P. Bio: Season One}}</ref> and in Australia on Region 4 DVD on June 6, 2019 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jbhifi.com.au/movies-tv-shows/movies-tv-shows-on-sale/tv-comedy/a-p-bio-season-1/384912/|title=A.P. Bio - Season 1 3 DVD}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|URL=https://www.nbc.com/ap-bio}}\n*{{IMDb title|6461726}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|United States}}\n\n{{Peacock (streaming service)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:A.P. Bio}}\n[[Category:2010s American high school television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American workplace comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Broadway Video]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Toledo, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Peacock (streaming service) original programming]]\n", "name_user": "WavSlave", "label": "safe", "comment": "Original text made no sense, at least to me", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A.P._Bio"}
{"title_page": "Dorothea Jordan", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dorothea Jordan\n| image              = Jordan by Hoppner.jpg\n| caption            = ''Mrs. Jordan in the Character of [[Hippolyta]]'', painting by [[John Hoppner]], first exhibited 1791 (previously in the [[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] and [[Tate Britain|Tate]] collections, now on loan to the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arthistorynews.com/articles/3237_Exclusive__Museum_swapshop|title=Exclusive - Museum swap-shop - Art History News - by Bendor Grosvenor|first=Blog Design and Build by Duncan Marshall and Conrad Barrett-Freeman at Chroma Design.|last=www.chromadesign.co.uk|website=www.arthistorynews.com}}</ref>)\n| other_names        = Dorothea Phillips,  Dora Jordan, Madame James\n| birth_name         = Dorothea Bland\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1761|11|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[County Waterford]], [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| death_place        = [[Saint-Cloud]], [[Bourbon Restoration|France]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1816|7|5|1761|11|21|df=y}}\n| occupation         = Actress and courtesan\n| partner            = [[Richard Daly]]<br>Charles Doyne<br>[[Tate Wilkinson]]<br>George Inchbald<br>Richard Ford<br>[[William IV of the United Kingdom]]\n| children           = [[Frances Alsop]]<br>Dorothea Maria March<br>Lady Lucy Hester Hawker<br>[[George FitzClarence, 1st Earl of Munster]]<br>[[Henry FitzClarence]]<br>[[Sophia Sidney, Baroness De L'Isle and Dudley]]<br>[[Lady Mary Fox]]<br>[[Lord Frederick FitzClarence]]<br>[[Elizabeth Hay, Countess of Erroll]]<br>[[Lord Adolphus FitzClarence]]<br>[[Lady Augusta Gordon|Lady Augusta Hallyburton]]<br>[[Lord Augustus FitzClarence]]<br>[[Amelia Cary, Viscountess Falkland]]\n}}\n\n'''Dorothea Jordan''' (21 November 1761{{snd}}5 July 1816), also known interchangeably as '''Mrs Jordan''' and previously '''Miss Francis''' or '''Miss Bland''', was an [[Anglo-Irish]] actress, [[courtesan]] and the [[mistress (lover)|mistress]] and companion of the future King [[William IV of the United Kingdom]] for 20 years (1791\u20131811) while he was [[Duke of Clarence]]. Together they had ten illegitimate children, all of whom took the surname ''[[FitzClarence]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nDorothea (often called '''Dorothy''' or '''Dora''') Bland was born near [[Waterford]] City in [[Ireland]] on 22 November 1761<ref> \"Dorothea Jordan\", Encyclopeadia Britannica Online. https://www.britannica.com/biography/Dorothea-Jordan Retrieved 11th February, 2020.</ref>, and was baptised at [[St Martin in the Fields]], Middlesex, on 5 December of that year.<ref name =\"Camp\">[http://anthonyjcamp.com/page13.htm Anthony J. Camp: ''Ancestry of Mrs Jordan''] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref> She was the third of six children born from Francis Bland (b. 1736{{snd}}d. Dover, 2 January 1778) and his mistress, Grace Phillips (b. ca. 1740{{snd}}d. Edinburgh, 1789). Her older siblings are George Bland ({{circa|1758}}{{snd}}Boston, Massachusetts, 1807; actor and singer) and Hester Bland (baptised at St Anne Soho, Middlesex, 2 March 1760{{snd}}buried at St David's, as of Trelethin, 8 March 1848), and her younger siblings are Lucy Bland (1763/64{{snd}}Trelethin, St David's, 1778, aged 14), Francis Bland ({{fl.|1813}}; a captain, unmarried and without issue) and Nathaniel Phillips Bland (born 1766/67{{snd}}buried at St David's, Pembrokeshire, 3 June 1830, aged 63).<ref name =\"Camp\"/>\n\nHer paternal grandparents were Nathaniel Bland (Killarney, co. Kerry, 1695/96{{snd}}1760), [[Vicar General]] of [[Ardfert]] and [[Aghada]], and Judge of the [[Prerogative Court]] of [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]], and his second wife Lucy (n\u00e9e Heaton).<ref name =\"Camp\"/> The reports about Dorothea's maternal ancestry  are very sketchy, although it is generally stated that Grace Phillips was probably the daughter of a Welsh clergyman (who lived in the early 1750s in Bristol) but he has not been identified with certainty.<ref name =\"Camp\"/>\n\nBefore April 1774, when she was 13, Dorothea's father, who worked as a stagehand, abandoned the family<ref name =\"Camp\"/> to marry an Irish actress. However, he continued to support the family by sending them meagre sums of money. This allowance was on the condition that the children would not use his last name. <ref name=\"odnb\">{{Cite ODNB|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-15119|title=Jordan, Dorothy [real name Dorothy Phillips] (1761\u20131816), actress {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/15119|access-date=2019-10-24|year=2004}}</ref> Dorothea then adopted her mother's maiden name, Phillips. This situation forced Dorothea to work to help her siblings. Her mother, an actress by profession, saw potential in Dorothea and put her on the stage. Dora became a famous actress and was said to have the most beautiful legs ever seen on the stage.\n\n\n==Theatrical career ==\nThe historical record of Jordan's first stage appearance is not clear. Some sources claim that Jordan made her debut in 1777 in [[Dublin]], as Phoebe in ''[[As You Like It]],'' whilst others that suggest she premiered as Lucy in the Interlude ''The Virgin Unmask'd,'' on the 3rd November 1779.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A biographical dictionary of actors, actresses, musicians, dancers, managers & other stage personnel in London, 1660-1800. Volume 10, M'Intosh to Nash|last=1918-2014|first=Highfill, Philip H., Jr. (Philip Henry)|others=Burnim, Kalman A.,, Langhans, Edward A.|isbn=9780585030326|location=Carbondale|oclc=44959689}}</ref> The knowledge of Jordans's time and other roles performed in Ireland is fragmentary, however she is known to have played Priscilla Tomboy in Bickerstaff's ''The Romp,'' Anne in ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'', and Adelaide in the tragedy, ''The Count of Narbonne.''<ref name=\"odnb\" /> With the Smock Alley Theatre, under the management of Richard Daley, Jordan began playing male roles in the company's 'reversed' cast. Documentation shows her last appearance in Dublin came on the 16th May 1782 when she spoke the ''The Maid of Oaks'''  Prologue''.'' At the time she was pregnant with the illegitimate child of the married theatre manager of the Smock Alley Theatre, Richard Daly.  \n\nRumours spread and she fled to England, specifically [[Leeds]], where she was employed by [[Tate Wilkinson]], manager of the York Company.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Life of Mrs Jordan, Volume 2 : Including Original Private Correspondence, and Numerous Anecdotes of her Contemporaries|last=James|first=Boaden|isbn=9781139452915|location=Cambridge|oclc=967377202}}</ref> It was during this move that she adopted the surname 'Jordan,' and like all the other women in the company (both unmarried and married), adopted the title \"Mrs.\" Her first performance in England was the tragic role of Calista in ''[[The Fair Penitent]],''  on 11 July 1782 for which she had been tutored for by the scholar Cornelious Swan.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Mrs Jordan's profession|last=Claire.|first=Tomalin|date=2012|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9780241963296|location=London|oclc=779244420}}</ref> Wilkinson paid her 15 shillings a week and she quickly won over the favour of her audiences, packing theatres.  Despite the actresses versatile acting talents, the critics were not pleased with her performing tragedy roles. Dora was faced harsh criticism from these roles as she was not considered socially acceptable to play women of a higher standing.<ref>Mrs Jordan (Dorothy Jordan). (18<sup>th</sup>-20<sup>th</sup> century). (Album containing press cuttings, exhibition catalogue: 'Mrs Jordan: The Duchess of Drury Lane', 1995); engraved portraits; article; sheet music ('The Willow'), press cuttings, book extract and poster.) University of Bristol, Theatre Collection. Bristol, United Kingdom.</ref> Swan wrote to Tate to express his amazement at Jordan's talents: <blockquote>'''\u2018'''''\u201cFor really Wilkinson,\u201d said he, \u201cI have given the Jordan but three lessons, and she is so adroit at receiving my instructions, that I declare she repeats the character as well as [[Susannah Maria Cibber|Mrs. Cibber]] ever did\u201d\u2019'' <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Women and Shakespeare in the eighteenth century|last=Fiona.|first=Ritchie|isbn=9781107046306|location=New York, NY|oclc=855957476|date = 2 June 2014}}</ref></blockquote>Jordan performed in the Yorkshire Circuit with Wilkinson's company for three years from 1782\u20131785. <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Mrs. Jordan's profession : the actress and the prince|last=Tomalin, Claire.|date=1995|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|isbn=0-679-41071-6|edition=1st American|location=New York|oclc=30895329|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mrsjordansprofes00toma}}</ref> Jordan was able to learn her lines quickly and seemed to have a natural talent, which made the other actresses in the company jealous. In her first few months, she was given the role of Fanny in ''The Clandestine Marriage'', which only made her more unpopular with the women in the company.  \n\nDuring this first tour, while in Hull, Jordan gave birth to her first daughter Frances. After the delivery, while Jordan cared for the baby, the actresses of the company \"blackened her character among the people of Hull.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> When Jordan returned to the stage on Boxing Day playing Calista in ''The Fair Penitent'', she was met with strong disapproval. Audiences felt that the similarities between Jordan and Calista were too similar. However, Wilkinson came to Jordan's aid to distill the gossip, painting Jordan as a mild mannered victim. Through Wilkinson's support and Jordan's hard work and good nature, she was eventually able to win over the people before they returned to York.  \n\nSome time later, while in York, [[Sarah Siddons]] came to visit with Wilkinson and see Dora Jordan perform in one of her popular breeches roles. Siddons however, was not impressed with Jordan's performance, and said that Jordan should remain on the Yorkshire Circuit, for she was \"not up to London.\" <ref name=\":5\" /> This remark, was soon discounted when William Smith came from London and offered Jordan a salary of \u00a34 a week at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]]. She took the offer and performed for Wilkinson's company for a final time on 9 September 1785 before departing to London with her mother, two-year-old daughter and sister Hester.  \n\nThough no specific dates can be sourced, Dora is believed to have performed the role of Lady Teazle in Sheridan's [[The School for Scandal]] before she arrived in London.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Piozzi letters : correspondence of Hester Lynch Piozzi, 1784-1821 (formerly Mrs. Thrale)|last=Piozzi|first= Hester Lynch|date=|publisher=University of Delaware Press|others=Bloom, Edward A. (Edward Alan), 1914-1994., Bloom, Lillian D.|isbn=0874131154|location=Newark|oclc=17441329}} \u00a91989-\u00a92002</ref> In 1785, she made her first [[London]] appearance at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]] as Peggy in ''[[A Country Girl]]''. The Morning post the next morning reported her performance as such: <blockquote>'''Nature has endowed her with talents sufficient to combat and excel her competitors in the same walk. Her person and manner are adapted for representing the peculiarities of youthful innocence and frivolity; and her tones of voice are audible and melodious''.'.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molloy|first=J. Fitzgerald|date=April 1892|title=Dorothy Jordan|url=https://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=TN_proquest3238002&context=PC&vid=44BU_VU1&search_scope=default_scope&tab=default_tab&lang=en_US|journal=The English Illustrated Magazine|volume=103|pages=567\u2013571|via=ProQuest}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Portrait of Mrs. Jordan, as Peggy (4673969).jpg|thumb|Mrs. Jordan in her role of Peggy in \"[[The Country Girl (1766 play)|The Country Girl]]\", [[David Garrick]]'s tamer adaption of [[William Wycherley|Wycherley]]'s earlier, more scandalous play \"[[The Country Wife]]\". ]]\nGradually, it came to be recognised that her talent lay in comedy. She was acclaimed for her \"naturalness\" on stage, and called a 'child of nature',<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Perry|first=Gillian|date=2004-10-11|title=Staging Gender and \"Hairy Signs\": Representing Dorothy Jordan's Curls|journal=Eighteenth-Century Studies|language=en|volume=38|issue=1|pages=145\u2013163|doi=10.1353/ecs.2004.0061|issn=1086-315X}}</ref> a slightly derogatory term for someone who is of illegitimate birth.<ref name=\":2\" /> Audiences also enjoyed her performances in [[breeches role]]s<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Denlinger\n  | first = Elizabeth Campbell\n  | title = Before Victoria: extraordinary women of the British romantic era\n  | publisher = Columbia University Press\n  | year = 2005\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dVIGcfOMwn8C&pg=PA81\n  | isbn = 978-0-231-13630-3}}\n</ref> such as Viola in [[Twelfth Night]],<ref name=\":1\" /> Sir Harry Wildair in The Constant Couple and William in ''[[Rosina (opera)|Rosina]]''. \"\n\nDespite her being 'the most admired comic actress of her time',<ref name=\":0\" /> Jordan was also a competent Shakespearean and tragic actress, playing the roles of [[Ophelia]], Imogen in [[Cymbeline]], Emilia in [[Othello]] and Zara by Adam Hill.<ref name=\":1\" /> When she first auditioned for Wilkinson, when she was asked whether she preferred 'tragedy, comedy or opera?' she answered \"All\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The life of Mrs. Jordan: including original private correspondence, and numerous anecdotes of her contemporaries|last=Boaden|first=James|publisher=Edward Bull, Holles Street|year=1831|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n\nPlay them \"all\" she did, though, Jordan found less success in playing women of higher social standing with some individuals believing that she lacked the \"artifice and incisiveness\" of other actresses who commonly played high standing female roles. <ref name=\"odnb\"/>\n\nIn addition to playing at Drury Lane and Covent Garden, Jordan continued to return to the provincial circuits. She returned to Wilkinson's Circuit in [[York]] several times, as well [[Edinburgh]], [[Margate]], [[Liverpool]], [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Bristol]] and [[Manchester]]. \n\nHer engagement at Drury Lane lasted until 1809, and she played a large variety of parts. During the rebuilding of Drury Lane she played at the Haymarket; she transferred her services in 1811 to Covent Garden. Here, in 1814, she made her last appearance on the London stage, and the following year, at Margate, retired altogether.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Jordan, Dorothea|volume=15|pages=508\u2013509}}</ref>\n\nDuring her time on the stage she wrote the popular song [[Bluebells of Scotland|The Bluebells of Scotland]], published under her name around 1800.<ref>British Musical Biography: A Dictionary of Musical Artists, Authors, and Composers Born in Britain and Its Colonies, James Duff Brown and Stephen Samuel Stratton, Birmingham, England: S. S. Stratton, 1897, p. 225</ref>\n\nIn 1815, the renowned theatre critic, William Hazlitt, wrote: <blockquote>''<nowiki/>'Mrs Jordan's excellences were all natural to her. It was not as an actress, but as herself, that she charmed everyone. Nature had formed in her most prodigal humour; and when nature is in the humour to make a woman all that is delightful, she does it most effectually. . . Mrs Jordan, the child of nature, whose voice was a cordial to the heart, because it came from it, rich, full, like the luscious juice of the rich grape.'''<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Early Relationships ==\nShe had an affair with her first manager, [[Richard Daly (actor)|Richard Daly]], the [[Management|manager]] of the [[Theatre Royal, Cork]], who was married, and had an illegitimate child with him:\n\n* [[Frances Alsop|Frances Daly]] (also called ''Fanny''; born in September 1782; she later changed her name to ''Frances Bettesworth'' in 1806 and married Thomas Alsop in 1809).<ref>Separated from her husband, she became an actress like her mother and died (probably from an overdose of laudanum) in America in 1821. [https://books.google.com/books?id=mjeImcc9rGwC&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259&dq=frances+daly+1782+dorothea+ford&source=bl&ots=L5GZUJJhwr&sig=YbXBrwTBx3ZewH8XKCFfa5HKlsg&hl=es&sa=X&ei=UgiBVNb1K8y2yATl7IK4Bg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=frances%20daly%201782%20dorothea%20ford&f=false Philip H. Highfill, Kalman A. Burnim, Edward A. Langhans: ''A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and others Stage Personnel in London'', vol. 8: ''Hough to Keyse'', p. 259.]; [https://books.google.com/books?id=DAqh7z7OYW0C&pg=PA112&lpg=PA112&dq=frances+daly+1782&source=bl&ots=Vdl3Ikm5tV&sig=Z9fAGbUa6ZX1ZOSNmDTaCSycnsE&hl=es&sa=X&ei=1geBVJyFL82tyATa_IGgAQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=frances%20daly%201782&f=false Wendy C. Nielsen: ''Women Warriors in Romantic Drama'', Chapter IV, p. 112.] [retrieved 4 December 2014]; [http://imagesearch.library.illinois.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/actors&CISOPTR=1990&CISOBOX=1&REC=6 ''Portrait of Mrs. Frances Bettesworth Alsop, ca. 1817'' in: Library of University of Illinois at Urbania-Champaign.] [retrieved 5 December 2014].</ref>\n\nDorothea's work with Richard Daly helped establish her as an actress in Dublin until the two separated and she left for England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4zg6kj6s?urlappend=%3Bseq=145|title=The Thespian dictionary; or, Dramatic biography of the eighteenth century; containing sketches of the lives, productions, &c., of all the principal managers, ...|website=HathiTrust|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> \n\nIn England, she had a short-lived affair with an army lieutenant, Charles Doyne, who proposed marriage. But she turned him down and went to work for the theatre company operated by [[Tate Wilkinson]]. It was at this point she adopted the name \"Mrs. Jordan\" \u2013 a reference to her escape across the [[Irish Sea]], likened to the [[River Jordan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sergeant |first1=Philip Walsingham |title=Mrs. Jordan: Child of Nature |url=https://archive.org/details/mrsjordanchildof00sergrich |date=1913 |publisher=Hutchinson & Company |page=[https://archive.org/details/mrsjordanchildof00sergrich/page/52 52] |language=en}}</ref> The name \"Mrs Jordan\" was <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4zg6kj6s?urlappend=%3Bseq=145|title=The Thespian dictionary; or, Dramatic biography of the eighteenth century; containing sketches of the lives, productions, &c., of all the principal managers, ...|website=HathiTrust|language=en|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>also reportedly was given to her by Richard Daly for 'motherly reasons', soon after she gave birth to their first illegitimate child. She appeared at Wilkinson's York Circuit theatres, including [[The Theatre, Leeds]], where she complained of uncomfortable working conditions.<ref name=\"Leodis\" >[http://www.leodis.net/discovery/discovery.asp?pageno=&page=2003218_251720608&topic=2003219_253704250&subsection=2003625_449382961 Leodis, Discovering Leeds: The Theatre] Retrieved 17 December 2013</ref> \n\nShortly after her affair with Wilkinson was over, she began an affair with George Inchbald, the male lead in the Wilkinson company. According to [[Claire Tomalin]], Dorothea's biographer, Dorothea would have married Inchbald, so greatly was she in love with him, but he never asked. Brokenhearted, she left him in 1786 to begin an affair with Sir Richard Ford, a police [[magistrate]] and a lawyer. She moved in with Ford when he promised to marry her. They had three illegitimate children:<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mjeImcc9rGwC&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259&dq=frances+daly+1782+dorothea+ford&source=bl&ots=L5GZUJJhwr&sig=YbXBrwTBx3ZewH8XKCFfa5HKlsg&hl=es&sa=X&ei=UgiBVNb1K8y2yATl7IK4Bg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=frances%20daly%201782%20dorothea%20ford&f=false Philip H. Highfill, Kalman A. Burnim, Edward A. Langhans: ''A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and others Stage Personnel in London'', vol. 8: ''Hough to Keyse'', p. 259.] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref> \n*Dorothea Maria Ford (born August 1787, married Frederick Edward March in 1809).<ref>According to Anthony Camp, she was a mistress of the Duke of Clarence for some time after her marriage. [http://anthonyjcamp.com/page8.htm Anthony J. Camp: ''Royal Mistresses and Bastards, No. 15-24''] [retrieved 5 December 2014].</ref>\n*A son (who died at birth in October or November 1788).\n*Lucy Hester Ford (born 1789, married Samuel Hawker\u2014later General and Sir\u2014in 1810).\n\nShe left him to begin her affair with the Duke of Clarence, once she realized that Ford was never going to marry her.<ref>pg. 90 & 91, Ladies of the Bedchamber, Dennis Friedman</ref> Jordan's children were placed under the care of her sister Hester, who moved with them to a house in Brompton. By a settlement dated 4 November 1791, Jordan transferred all her savings to Ford and Hester for the maintenance and education of the children; in addition, she allowed them an annual payment and granted Hester an allowance for her services.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CDuCchT6PE0C&pg=PA693&lpg=PA693&dq=dorothea+maria+ford+lucy+hester+ford&source=bl&ots=1FKoLxEpQE&sig=x_q5jgRKsDnLt7Tci-znNUcs5PE&hl=es&sa=X&ei=RA-BVLPBDZCNyASmtoC4Cg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dorothea%20maria%20ford%20lucy%20hester%20ford&f=false ''The Encyclopedia of Romantic Literature'', p. 693.] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mjeImcc9rGwC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=dorothea+maria+ford+lucy+hester+ford&source=bl&ots=L5GZUJLeEo&sig=7-CDQWjvWIA3QB_thpkvxaENsJw&hl=es&sa=X&ei=RA-BVLPBDZCNyASmtoC4Cg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dorothea%20maria%20ford%20lucy%20hester%20ford&f=false Philip H. Highfill, Kalman A. Burnim, Edward A. Langhans: ''A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and others Stage Personnel in London'', vol. 8: ''Hough to Keyse'', p. 253.] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref>\n\n== Relationship with William IV ==\nPretty, witty and intelligent, Jordan soon came to the attention of wealthy men. She became the mistress of William, Duke of Clarence, later [[William IV of the United Kingdom|King William IV]], in 1790, after he had taken notice to her at Drury Lane. Jordan began living with him first at Clarence Lodge and later, in 1797, at [[Bushy House]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4qlUWvVCnwIC&pg=PA212&lpg=PA212&dq=%22Dorothy+Jordan%22+AND+%22Bushy+House%22&source=bl&ots=njv_1_XIIS&sig=5ttzHN4cEnPGTXvov1FyrnM1AWs Google Books] ''The Story of Dorothy Jordan'' Armstrong, Clare & Jerrold, Bridgman. Ayer Publishing, 1969. {{ISBN|0-405-08672-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-405-08672-4}}\n</ref> and seemed to have not bothered herself with politics or the political intrigues that often went on behind the scenes in royal courts. Together they had at least ten [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] children, all of whom took the surname [[FitzClarence]]:\n\n*[[George FitzClarence, 1st Earl of Munster|George FitzClarence]] (29 January 1794{{snd}}20 March 1842), created [[Earl of Munster]] in 1831. Married Mary Wyndham.\n*[[Henry FitzClarence|Henry Edward FitzClarence]] (27 March 1795{{snd}}September 1817). Unmarried.\n*[[Sophia Sidney, Baroness De L'Isle and Dudley|Sophia FitzClarence]] (August 1796{{snd}}10 April 1837), married [[Philip Sidney, 1st Baron De L'Isle and Dudley]].\n*[[Lady Mary Fox|Mary FitzClarence]] (19 December 1798{{snd}}13 July 1864), married General [[Charles Richard Fox]]. No issue.\n*[[Lieutenant General]] [[Lord Frederick FitzClarence]] [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]] (9 December 1799{{snd}}30 October 1854), officer in the [[British Army]]. Married Lady Augusta Boyle. \n*[[Elizabeth Hay, Countess of Erroll|Elizabeth FitzClarence]] (17 January 1801{{snd}}16 January 1856), married [[William Hay, 18th Earl of Erroll]].\n*[[Rear-Admiral]] [[Lord Adolphus FitzClarence]] [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Royal Navy|RN]] (18 February 1802{{snd}}17 May 1856). Unmarried. \n*[[Lady Augusta Gordon|Augusta FitzClarence]] (17 November 1803{{snd}}8 December 1865) married, firstly, Hon. [[John Kennedy-Erskine]], 5 July 1827, married secondly, Admiral [[Lord Frederick Gordon-Hallyburton]].\n*[[Lord Augustus FitzClarence]] (1 March 1805{{snd}}14 June 1854), rector at [[Mapledurham]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. Married Sarah Elizabeth Catharine Gordon.\n*[[Amelia Cary, Viscountess Falkland|Amelia FitzClarence]] (21 March 1807{{snd}}2 July 1858), married [[Lucius Bentinck Cary, 10th Viscount Falkland]].\n\nDuring this time, Jordan was given a yearly stipend of \u00a31200, though she continued to perform at both Drury Lane and Covent Garden, as well as on provincial tours until their separation. \n\n==Later life==\nIn 1811, after a 21-year relationship Jordan and the Duke separated due to pressures from his family to find a suitable wife, as he was heir to the throne.<ref>Mrs Jordan (Dorothy Jordan). (18<sup>th</sup>-20<sup>th</sup> century). (Album containing press cuttings, exhibition catalogue: 'Mrs Jordan: The Duchess of Drury Lane', 1995); engraved portraits; article; sheet music ('The Willow'), press cuttings, book extract and poster.) University of Bristol, Theatre Collection. Bristol, United Kingdom.</ref> Dorothea was given a yearly stipend of \u00a34,400 by him and custody of their daughters while he retained custody of their sons. \u00a32,200 of her stipend included money for the care of the children with a stipulation stating that in order to continue receiving that money, and retain custody, Dorothea must not return to the stage.<ref name=\"odnb\"/>\n\nIn 1814, when her son-in-law, Thomas Alsop, became heavily in debt, Dorothea returned to the stage to help pay off that debt. Once the Duke received word of this, he removed their remaining daughters from her care, and took back her yearly stipend. Dora had written letters to British theatre's and newspapers pleading with them to rehire her, acknowledging her prior mistress behaviour, expanding her celebrity status.<ref>Mrs Jordan (Dorothy Jordan). (18<sup>th</sup>-20<sup>th</sup> century). (Album containing press cuttings, exhibition catalogue: 'Mrs Jordan: The Duchess of Drury Lane', 1995); engraved portraits; article; sheet music ('The Willow'), press cuttings, book extract and poster.) University of Bristol, Theatre Collection. Bristol, United Kingdom.</ref>  \n\nUpon retiring from the stage in 1815, Jordan sold her house and moved to Boulogne, France under the name Mrs James or Madame James or Mrs Johnson, intending for the move to be a short stay. She lived frugally but always paid her rent on time. Not having been summoned back to England, she moved to Versailles by the end of the year. Soon after, she moved to [[Saint-Cloud]], near Paris. It is suggested that she made these last two moved to be closer to her son Frederick, who was stationed in Paris as part of the British Army. While in France, she was defrauded by eldest daughter, Frances and son-in-law, Thomas Alsop after they accumulated large sums of debt in her name. During this time, both her mental and physical health was declining. Her health was worsening and she suffered from \u2018bilious attacks, pains in her side, swollen ankles, shortness of breath and increasing general weakness\u2019. She missed her children terribly and confessed in a letter that \u201cits is not, believe me, the feelings of pride, avarice, or the absence of those comforts I have all my life been accustomed to, that is killing me by inches; it is the loss of my only remaining comfort, the hope I used to live on from time to time, of seeing my children\u201d. She died alone and in poverty on 5 July 1816 from a ruptured blood vessel caused by violent inflammation of the chest and was buried in the town cemetery.<ref name=\"odnb\"/><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/mrsjordansprofes00toma|title=Mrs Jordan's profession : the story of a great actress and a future King|last=Tomalin, Claire, 1933-|date=1994|publisher=Viking|isbn=0670841595|location=London|oclc=31377468|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Mrs. Jordan's Profession: The Actress and the Prince'', [[Claire Tomalin]], 17 October 1994, Publisher: Viking, {{ISBN|0-670-84159-5}}\n*''Ladies of the Bedchamber'', Dennis Friedman, 2003, Publisher: Peter Owen, {{ISBN|0-7206-1244-6}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRGJhWpf2qcC&pg=PA177 The Delectable Dora Jordan], In Otis Skinner (1928) ''Mad Folk of the Theatre'' Publisher: Ayer Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0-8369-1851-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jordan, Dorothea}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1816 deaths]]\n[[Category:FitzClarence family|*]]\n[[Category:18th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:19th-century English women]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Irish people]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English courtesans]]\n[[Category:Irish courtesans]]\n[[Category:Mistresses of British royalty]]\n[[Category:People from County Waterford]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriates in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dorothea Jordan\n| image              = Jordan by Hoppner.jpg\n| caption            = ''Mrs. Jordan in the Character of [[Hippolyta]]'', painting by [[John Hoppner]], first exhibited 1791 (previously in the [[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] and [[Tate Britain|Tate]] collections, now on loan to the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arthistorynews.com/articles/3237_Exclusive__Museum_swapshop|title=Exclusive - Museum swap-shop - Art History News - by Bendor Grosvenor|first=Blog Design and Build by Duncan Marshall and Conrad Barrett-Freeman at Chroma Design.|last=www.chromadesign.co.uk|website=www.arthistorynews.com}}</ref>)\n| other_names        = Dorothea Phillips,  Dora Jordan, Madame James\n| birth_name         = Dorothea Bland\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1761|11|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[County Waterford]], [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| death_place        = [[Saint-Cloud]], [[Bourbon Restoration|France]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1816|7|5|1761|11|21|df=y}}\n| occupation         = Actress and courtesan\n| partner            = [[Richard Daly]]<br>Charles Doyne<br>[[Tate Wilkinson]]<br>George Inchbald<br>Richard Ford<br>[[William IV of the United Kingdom]]\n| children           = [[Frances Alsop]]<br>Dorothea Maria March<br>Lady Lucy Hester Hawker<br>[[George FitzClarence, 1st Earl of Munster]]<br>[[Henry FitzClarence]]<br>[[Sophia Sidney, Baroness De L'Isle and Dudley]]<br>[[Lady Mary Fox]]<br>[[Lord Frederick FitzClarence]]<br>[[Elizabeth Hay, Countess of Erroll]]<br>[[Lord Adolphus FitzClarence]]<br>[[Lady Augusta Gordon|Lady Augusta Hallyburton]]<br>[[Lord Augustus FitzClarence]]<br>[[Amelia Cary, Viscountess Falkland]]\n}}\n\n'''Dorothea Jordan''' (21 November 1761{{snd}}5 July 1816), also known interchangeably as '''Mrs Jordan''' and previously '''Miss Francis''' or '''Miss Bland''', was an [[Anglo-Irish]] actress, [[courtesan]] and the [[mistress (lover)|mistress]] and companion of the future King [[William IV of the United Kingdom]] for 20 years (1791\u20131811) while he was [[Duke of Clarence]]. Together they had ten illegitimate children, all of whom took the surname ''[[FitzClarence]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nDorothea (often called '''Dorothy''' or '''Dora''') Bland was born near [[Waterford]] City in [[Ireland]] on 22 November 1761<ref> \"Dorothea Jordan\", Encyclopeadia Britannica Online. https://www.britannica.com/biography/Dorothea-Jordan Retrieved 11th February, 2020.</ref>, and was baptised at [[St Martin in the Fields]], Middlesex, on 5 December of that year.<ref name =\"Camp\">[http://anthonyjcamp.com/page13.htm Anthony J. Camp: ''Ancestry of Mrs Jordan''] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref> She was the third of six children born from Francis Bland (b. 1736{{snd}}d. Dover, 2 January 1778) and his mistress, Grace Phillips (b. ca. 1740{{snd}}d. Edinburgh, 1789). Her older siblings are George Bland ({{circa|1758}}{{snd}}Boston, Massachusetts, 1807; actor and singer) and Hester Bland (baptised at St Anne Soho, Middlesex, 2 March 1760{{snd}}buried at St David's, as of Trelethin, 8 March 1848), and her younger siblings are Lucy Bland (1763/64{{snd}}Trelethin, St David's, 1778, aged 14), Francis Bland ({{fl.|1813}}; a captain, unmarried and without issue) and Nathaniel Phillips Bland (born 1766/67{{snd}}buried at St David's, Pembrokeshire, 3 June 1830, aged 63).<ref name =\"Camp\"/>\n\nHer paternal grandparents were Nathaniel Bland (Killarney, co. Kerry, 1695/96{{snd}}1760), [[Vicar General]] of [[Ardfert]] and [[Aghada]], and Judge of the [[Prerogative Court]] of [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]], and his second wife Lucy (n\u00e9e Heaton).<ref name =\"Camp\"/> The reports about Dorothea's maternal ancestry  are very sketchy, although it is generally stated that Grace Phillips was probably the daughter of a Welsh clergyman (who lived in the early 1750s in Bristol) but he has not been identified with certainty.<ref name =\"Camp\"/>\n\nBefore April 1774, when she was 13, Dorothea's father, who worked as a stagehand, abandoned the family<ref name =\"Camp\"/> to marry an Irish actress. However, he continued to support the family by sending them meagre sums of money. This allowance was on the condition that the children would not use his last name. <ref name=\"odnb\">{{Cite ODNB|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-15119|title=Jordan, Dorothy [real name Dorothy Phillips] (1761\u20131816), actress {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/15119|access-date=2019-10-24|year=2004}}</ref> Dorothea then adopted her mother's maiden name, Phillips. This situation forced Dorothea to work to help her siblings. Her mother, an actress by profession, saw potential in Dorothea and put her on the stage. Dora became a famous actress and was said to have the most beautiful legs ever seen on the stage.\n\n\n==Theatrical career ==\nThe historical record of Jordan's first stage appearance is not clear. Some sources claim that Jordan made her debut in 1777 in [[Dublin]], as Phoebe in ''[[As You Like It]],'' whilst others that suggest she premiered as Lucy in the Interlude ''The Virgin Unmask'd,'' on the 3rd November 1779.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A biographical dictionary of actors, actresses, musicians, dancers, managers & other stage personnel in London, 1660-1800. Volume 10, M'Intosh to Nash|last=1918-2014|first=Highfill, Philip H., Jr. (Philip Henry)|others=Burnim, Kalman A.,, Langhans, Edward A.|isbn=9780585030326|location=Carbondale|oclc=44959689}}</ref> The knowledge of Jordans's time and other roles performed in Ireland is fragmentary, however she is known to have played Priscilla Tomboy in Bickerstaff's ''The Romp,'' Anne in ''[[Richard III (play)|Richard III]]'', and Adelaide in the tragedy, ''The Count of Narbonne.''<ref name=\"odnb\" /> With the Smock Alley Theatre, under the management of Richard Daley, Jordan began playing male roles in the company's 'reversed' cast. Documentation shows her last appearance in Dublin came on the 16th May 1782 when she spoke the ''The Maid of Oaks'''  Prologue''.'' At the time she was pregnant with the illegitimate child of the married theatre manager of the Smock Alley Theatre, Richard Daly.  \n\nRumours spread and she fled to England, specifically [[Leeds]], where she was employed by [[Tate Wilkinson]], manager of the York Company.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Life of Mrs Jordan, Volume 2 : Including Original Private Correspondence, and Numerous Anecdotes of her Contemporaries|last=James|first=Boaden|isbn=9781139452915|location=Cambridge|oclc=967377202}}</ref> It was during this move that she adopted the surname 'Jordan,' and like all the other women in the company (both unmarried and married), adopted the title \"Mrs.\" Her first performance in England was the tragic role of Calista in ''[[The Fair Penitent]],''  on 11 July 1782 for which she had been tutored for by the scholar Cornelious Swan.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Mrs Jordan's profession|last=Claire.|first=Tomalin|date=2012|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9780241963296|location=London|oclc=779244420}}</ref> Wilkinson paid her 15 shillings a week and she quickly won over the favour of her audiences, packing theatres.  Despite the actresses versatile acting talents, the critics were not pleased with her performing tragedy roles. Dora was faced harsh criticism from these roles as she was not considered socially acceptable to play women of a higher standing.<ref>Mrs Jordan (Dorothy Jordan). (18<sup>th</sup>-20<sup>th</sup> century). (Album containing press cuttings, exhibition catalogue: 'Mrs Jordan: The Duchess of Drury Lane', 1995); engraved portraits; article; sheet music ('The Willow'), press cuttings, book extract and poster.) University of Bristol, Theatre Collection. Bristol, United Kingdom.</ref> Swan wrote to Tate to express his amazement at Jordan's talents: <blockquote>'''\u2018'''''\u201cFor really Wilkinson,\u201d said he, \u201cI have given the Jordan but three lessons, and she is so adroit at receiving my instructions, that I declare she repeats the character as well as [[Susannah Maria Cibber|Mrs. Cibber]] ever did\u201d\u2019'' <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Women and Shakespeare in the eighteenth century|last=Fiona.|first=Ritchie|isbn=9781107046306|location=New York, NY|oclc=855957476|date = 2 June 2014}}</ref></blockquote>Jordan performed in the Yorkshire Circuit with Wilkinson's company for three years from 1782\u20131785. <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Mrs. Jordan's profession : the actress and the prince|last=Tomalin, Claire.|date=1995|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|isbn=0-679-41071-6|edition=1st American|location=New York|oclc=30895329|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mrsjordansprofes00toma}}</ref> Jordan was able to learn her lines quickly and seemed to have a natural talent, which made the other actresses in the company jealous. In her first few months, she was given the role of Fanny in ''The Clandestine Marriage'', which only made her more unpopular with the women in the company.  \n\nDuring this first tour, while in Hull, Jordan gave birth to her first daughter Frances. After the delivery, while Jordan cared for the baby, the actresses of the company \"blackened her character among the people of Hull.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> When Jordan returned to the stage on Boxing Day playing Calista in ''The Fair Penitent'', she was met with strong disapproval. Audiences felt that the similarities between Jordan and Calista were too similar. However, Wilkinson come to Jordan's aid to distill the gossip, painting Jordan as a mild mannered victim. Through Wilkinson's support and Jordan's hard work and good nature, she was eventually able to win over the people before they returned to York.  \n\nSome time later, while in York, [[Sarah Siddons]] came to visit with Wilkinson and see Dora Jordan perform in one of her popular breeches roles. Siddons however, was not impressed with Jordan's performance, and said that Jordan should remain on the Yorkshire Circuit, for she was \"not up to London.\" <ref name=\":5\" /> This remark, was soon discounted when William Smith came from London and offered Jordan a salary of \u00a34 a week at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]]. She took the offer and performed for Wilkinson's company for a final time on 9 September 1785 before departing to London with her mother, two-year-old daughter and sister Hester.  \n\nThough no specific dates can be sourced, Dora is believed to have performed the role of Lady Teazle in Sheridan's [[The School for Scandal]] before she arrived in London.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Piozzi letters : correspondence of Hester Lynch Piozzi, 1784-1821 (formerly Mrs. Thrale)|last=Piozzi|first= Hester Lynch|date=|publisher=University of Delaware Press|others=Bloom, Edward A. (Edward Alan), 1914-1994., Bloom, Lillian D.|isbn=0874131154|location=Newark|oclc=17441329}} \u00a91989-\u00a92002</ref> In 1785, she made her first [[London]] appearance at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]] as Peggy in ''[[A Country Girl]]''. The Morning post the next morning reported her performance as such: <blockquote>'''Nature has endowed her with talents sufficient to combat and excel her competitors in the same walk. Her person and manner are adapted for representing the peculiarities of youthful innocence and frivolity; and her tones of voice are audible and melodious''.'.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Molloy|first=J. Fitzgerald|date=April 1892|title=Dorothy Jordan|url=https://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=TN_proquest3238002&context=PC&vid=44BU_VU1&search_scope=default_scope&tab=default_tab&lang=en_US|journal=The English Illustrated Magazine|volume=103|pages=567\u2013571|via=ProQuest}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Portrait of Mrs. Jordan, as Peggy (4673969).jpg|thumb|Mrs. Jordan in her role of Peggy in \"[[The Country Girl (1766 play)|The Country Girl]]\", [[David Garrick]]'s tamer adaption of [[William Wycherley|Wycherley]]'s earlier, more scandalous play \"[[The Country Wife]]\". ]]\nGradually, it came to be recognised that her talent lay in comedy. She was acclaimed for her \"naturalness\" on stage, and called a 'child of nature',<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Perry|first=Gillian|date=2004-10-11|title=Staging Gender and \"Hairy Signs\": Representing Dorothy Jordan's Curls|journal=Eighteenth-Century Studies|language=en|volume=38|issue=1|pages=145\u2013163|doi=10.1353/ecs.2004.0061|issn=1086-315X}}</ref> a slightly derogatory term for someone who is of illegitimate birth.<ref name=\":2\" /> Audiences also enjoyed her performances in [[breeches role]]s<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Denlinger\n  | first = Elizabeth Campbell\n  | title = Before Victoria: extraordinary women of the British romantic era\n  | publisher = Columbia University Press\n  | year = 2005\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dVIGcfOMwn8C&pg=PA81\n  | isbn = 978-0-231-13630-3}}\n</ref> such as Viola in [[Twelfth Night]],<ref name=\":1\" /> Sir Harry Wildair in The Constant Couple and William in ''[[Rosina (opera)|Rosina]]''. \"\n\nDespite her being 'the most admired comic actress of her time',<ref name=\":0\" /> Jordan was also a competent Shakespearean and tragic actress, playing the roles of [[Ophelia]], Imogen in [[Cymbeline]], Emilia in [[Othello]] and Zara by Adam Hill.<ref name=\":1\" /> When she first auditioned for Wilkinson, when she was asked whether she preferred 'tragedy, comedy or opera?' she answered \"All\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The life of Mrs. Jordan: including original private correspondence, and numerous anecdotes of her contemporaries|last=Boaden|first=James|publisher=Edward Bull, Holles Street|year=1831|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n\nPlay them \"all\" she did, though, Jordan found less success in playing women of higher social standing with some individuals believing that she lacked the \"artifice and incisiveness\" of other actresses who commonly played high standing female roles. <ref name=\"odnb\"/>\n\nIn addition to playing at Drury Lane and Covent Garden, Jordan continued to return to the provincial circuits. She returned to Wilkinson's Circuit in [[York]] several times, as well [[Edinburgh]], [[Margate]], [[Liverpool]], [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Bristol]] and [[Manchester]]. \n\nHer engagement at Drury Lane lasted until 1809, and she played a large variety of parts. During the rebuilding of Drury Lane she played at the Haymarket; she transferred her services in 1811 to Covent Garden. Here, in 1814, she made her last appearance on the London stage, and the following year, at Margate, retired altogether.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Jordan, Dorothea|volume=15|pages=508\u2013509}}</ref>\n\nDuring her time on the stage she wrote the popular song [[Bluebells of Scotland|The Bluebells of Scotland]], published under her name around 1800.<ref>British Musical Biography: A Dictionary of Musical Artists, Authors, and Composers Born in Britain and Its Colonies, James Duff Brown and Stephen Samuel Stratton, Birmingham, England: S. S. Stratton, 1897, p. 225</ref>\n\nIn 1815, the renowned theatre critic, William Hazlitt, wrote: <blockquote>''<nowiki/>'Mrs Jordan's excellences were all natural to her. It was not as an actress, but as herself, that she charmed everyone. Nature had formed in her most prodigal humour; and when nature is in the humour to make a woman all that is delightful, she does it most effectually. . . Mrs Jordan, the child of nature, whose voice was a cordial to the heart, because it came from it, rich, full, like the luscious juice of the rich grape.'''<ref name=\":2\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Early Relationships ==\nShe had an affair with her first manager, [[Richard Daly (actor)|Richard Daly]], the [[Management|manager]] of the [[Theatre Royal, Cork]], who was married, and had an illegitimate child with him:\n\n* [[Frances Alsop|Frances Daly]] (also called ''Fanny''; born in September 1782; she later changed her name to ''Frances Bettesworth'' in 1806 and married Thomas Alsop in 1809).<ref>Separated from her husband, she became an actress like her mother and died (probably from an overdose of laudanum) in America in 1821. [https://books.google.com/books?id=mjeImcc9rGwC&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259&dq=frances+daly+1782+dorothea+ford&source=bl&ots=L5GZUJJhwr&sig=YbXBrwTBx3ZewH8XKCFfa5HKlsg&hl=es&sa=X&ei=UgiBVNb1K8y2yATl7IK4Bg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=frances%20daly%201782%20dorothea%20ford&f=false Philip H. Highfill, Kalman A. Burnim, Edward A. Langhans: ''A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and others Stage Personnel in London'', vol. 8: ''Hough to Keyse'', p. 259.]; [https://books.google.com/books?id=DAqh7z7OYW0C&pg=PA112&lpg=PA112&dq=frances+daly+1782&source=bl&ots=Vdl3Ikm5tV&sig=Z9fAGbUa6ZX1ZOSNmDTaCSycnsE&hl=es&sa=X&ei=1geBVJyFL82tyATa_IGgAQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=frances%20daly%201782&f=false Wendy C. Nielsen: ''Women Warriors in Romantic Drama'', Chapter IV, p. 112.] [retrieved 4 December 2014]; [http://imagesearch.library.illinois.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/actors&CISOPTR=1990&CISOBOX=1&REC=6 ''Portrait of Mrs. Frances Bettesworth Alsop, ca. 1817'' in: Library of University of Illinois at Urbania-Champaign.] [retrieved 5 December 2014].</ref>\n\nDorothea's work with Richard Daly helped establish her as an actress in Dublin until the two separated and she left for England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4zg6kj6s?urlappend=%3Bseq=145|title=The Thespian dictionary; or, Dramatic biography of the eighteenth century; containing sketches of the lives, productions, &c., of all the principal managers, ...|website=HathiTrust|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> \n\nIn England, she had a short-lived affair with an army lieutenant, Charles Doyne, who proposed marriage. But she turned him down and went to work for the theatre company operated by [[Tate Wilkinson]]. It was at this point she adopted the name \"Mrs. Jordan\" \u2013 a reference to her escape across the [[Irish Sea]], likened to the [[River Jordan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sergeant |first1=Philip Walsingham |title=Mrs. Jordan: Child of Nature |url=https://archive.org/details/mrsjordanchildof00sergrich |date=1913 |publisher=Hutchinson & Company |page=[https://archive.org/details/mrsjordanchildof00sergrich/page/52 52] |language=en}}</ref> The name \"Mrs Jordan\" was <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4zg6kj6s?urlappend=%3Bseq=145|title=The Thespian dictionary; or, Dramatic biography of the eighteenth century; containing sketches of the lives, productions, &c., of all the principal managers, ...|website=HathiTrust|language=en|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>also reportedly was given to her by Richard Daly for 'motherly reasons', soon after she gave birth to their first illegitimate child. She appeared at Wilkinson's York Circuit theatres, including [[The Theatre, Leeds]], where she complained of uncomfortable working conditions.<ref name=\"Leodis\" >[http://www.leodis.net/discovery/discovery.asp?pageno=&page=2003218_251720608&topic=2003219_253704250&subsection=2003625_449382961 Leodis, Discovering Leeds: The Theatre] Retrieved 17 December 2013</ref> \n\nShortly after her affair with Wilkinson was over, she began an affair with George Inchbald, the male lead in the Wilkinson company. According to [[Claire Tomalin]], Dorothea's biographer, Dorothea would have married Inchbald, so greatly was she in love with him, but he never asked. Brokenhearted, she left him in 1786 to begin an affair with Sir Richard Ford, a police [[magistrate]] and a lawyer. She moved in with Ford when he promised to marry her. They had three illegitimate children:<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mjeImcc9rGwC&pg=PA259&lpg=PA259&dq=frances+daly+1782+dorothea+ford&source=bl&ots=L5GZUJJhwr&sig=YbXBrwTBx3ZewH8XKCFfa5HKlsg&hl=es&sa=X&ei=UgiBVNb1K8y2yATl7IK4Bg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=frances%20daly%201782%20dorothea%20ford&f=false Philip H. Highfill, Kalman A. Burnim, Edward A. Langhans: ''A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and others Stage Personnel in London'', vol. 8: ''Hough to Keyse'', p. 259.] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref> \n*Dorothea Maria Ford (born August 1787, married Frederick Edward March in 1809).<ref>According to Anthony Camp, she was a mistress of the Duke of Clarence for some time after her marriage. [http://anthonyjcamp.com/page8.htm Anthony J. Camp: ''Royal Mistresses and Bastards, No. 15-24''] [retrieved 5 December 2014].</ref>\n*A son (who died at birth in October or November 1788).\n*Lucy Hester Ford (born 1789, married Samuel Hawker\u2014later General and Sir\u2014in 1810).\n\nShe left him to begin her affair with the Duke of Clarence, once she realized that Ford was never going to marry her.<ref>pg. 90 & 91, Ladies of the Bedchamber, Dennis Friedman</ref> Jordan's children were placed under the care of her sister Hester, who moved with them to a house in Brompton. By a settlement dated 4 November 1791, Jordan transferred all her savings to Ford and Hester for the maintenance and education of the children; in addition, she allowed them an annual payment and granted Hester an allowance for her services.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CDuCchT6PE0C&pg=PA693&lpg=PA693&dq=dorothea+maria+ford+lucy+hester+ford&source=bl&ots=1FKoLxEpQE&sig=x_q5jgRKsDnLt7Tci-znNUcs5PE&hl=es&sa=X&ei=RA-BVLPBDZCNyASmtoC4Cg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dorothea%20maria%20ford%20lucy%20hester%20ford&f=false ''The Encyclopedia of Romantic Literature'', p. 693.] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mjeImcc9rGwC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=dorothea+maria+ford+lucy+hester+ford&source=bl&ots=L5GZUJLeEo&sig=7-CDQWjvWIA3QB_thpkvxaENsJw&hl=es&sa=X&ei=RA-BVLPBDZCNyASmtoC4Cg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dorothea%20maria%20ford%20lucy%20hester%20ford&f=false Philip H. Highfill, Kalman A. Burnim, Edward A. Langhans: ''A Biographical Dictionary of Actors, Actresses, Musicians, Dancers, Managers and others Stage Personnel in London'', vol. 8: ''Hough to Keyse'', p. 253.] [retrieved 4 December 2014].</ref>\n\n== Relationship with William IV ==\nPretty, witty and intelligent, Jordan soon came to the attention of wealthy men. She became the mistress of William, Duke of Clarence, later [[William IV of the United Kingdom|King William IV]], in 1790, after he had taken notice to her at Drury Lane. Jordan began living with him first at Clarence Lodge and later, in 1797, at [[Bushy House]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4qlUWvVCnwIC&pg=PA212&lpg=PA212&dq=%22Dorothy+Jordan%22+AND+%22Bushy+House%22&source=bl&ots=njv_1_XIIS&sig=5ttzHN4cEnPGTXvov1FyrnM1AWs Google Books] ''The Story of Dorothy Jordan'' Armstrong, Clare & Jerrold, Bridgman. Ayer Publishing, 1969. {{ISBN|0-405-08672-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-405-08672-4}}\n</ref> and seemed to have not bothered herself with politics or the political intrigues that often went on behind the scenes in royal courts. Together they had at least ten [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] children, all of whom took the surname [[FitzClarence]]:\n\n*[[George FitzClarence, 1st Earl of Munster|George FitzClarence]] (29 January 1794{{snd}}20 March 1842), created [[Earl of Munster]] in 1831. Married Mary Wyndham.\n*[[Henry FitzClarence|Henry Edward FitzClarence]] (27 March 1795{{snd}}September 1817). Unmarried.\n*[[Sophia Sidney, Baroness De L'Isle and Dudley|Sophia FitzClarence]] (August 1796{{snd}}10 April 1837), married [[Philip Sidney, 1st Baron De L'Isle and Dudley]].\n*[[Lady Mary Fox|Mary FitzClarence]] (19 December 1798{{snd}}13 July 1864), married General [[Charles Richard Fox]]. No issue.\n*[[Lieutenant General]] [[Lord Frederick FitzClarence]] [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]] (9 December 1799{{snd}}30 October 1854), officer in the [[British Army]]. Married Lady Augusta Boyle. \n*[[Elizabeth Hay, Countess of Erroll|Elizabeth FitzClarence]] (17 January 1801{{snd}}16 January 1856), married [[William Hay, 18th Earl of Erroll]].\n*[[Rear-Admiral]] [[Lord Adolphus FitzClarence]] [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]], [[Aide-de-camp|ADC]], [[Royal Navy|RN]] (18 February 1802{{snd}}17 May 1856). Unmarried. \n*[[Lady Augusta Gordon|Augusta FitzClarence]] (17 November 1803{{snd}}8 December 1865) married, firstly, Hon. [[John Kennedy-Erskine]], 5 July 1827, married secondly, Admiral [[Lord Frederick Gordon-Hallyburton]].\n*[[Lord Augustus FitzClarence]] (1 March 1805{{snd}}14 June 1854), rector at [[Mapledurham]] in [[Oxfordshire]]. Married Sarah Elizabeth Catharine Gordon.\n*[[Amelia Cary, Viscountess Falkland|Amelia FitzClarence]] (21 March 1807{{snd}}2 July 1858), married [[Lucius Bentinck Cary, 10th Viscount Falkland]].\n\nDuring this time, Jordan was given a yearly stipend of \u00a31200, though she continued to perform at both Drury Lane and Covent Garden, as well as on provincial tours until their separation. \n\n==Later life==\nIn 1811, after a 21-year relationship Jordan and the Duke separated due to pressures from his family to find a suitable wife, as he was heir to the throne.<ref>Mrs Jordan (Dorothy Jordan). (18<sup>th</sup>-20<sup>th</sup> century). (Album containing press cuttings, exhibition catalogue: 'Mrs Jordan: The Duchess of Drury Lane', 1995); engraved portraits; article; sheet music ('The Willow'), press cuttings, book extract and poster.) University of Bristol, Theatre Collection. Bristol, United Kingdom.</ref> Dorothea was given a yearly stipend of \u00a34,400 by him and custody of their daughters while he retained custody of their sons. \u00a32,200 of her stipend included money for the care of the children with a stipulation stating that in order to continue receiving that money, and retain custody, Dorothea must not return to the stage.<ref name=\"odnb\"/>\n\nIn 1814, when her son-in-law, Thomas Alsop, became heavily in debt, Dorothea returned to the stage to help pay off that debt. Once the Duke received word of this, he removed their remaining daughters from her care, and took back her yearly stipend. Dora had written letters to British theatre's and newspapers pleading with them to rehire her, acknowledging her prior mistress behaviour, expanding her celebrity status.<ref>Mrs Jordan (Dorothy Jordan). (18<sup>th</sup>-20<sup>th</sup> century). (Album containing press cuttings, exhibition catalogue: 'Mrs Jordan: The Duchess of Drury Lane', 1995); engraved portraits; article; sheet music ('The Willow'), press cuttings, book extract and poster.) University of Bristol, Theatre Collection. Bristol, United Kingdom.</ref>  \n\nUpon retiring from the stage in 1815, Jordan sold her house and moved to Boulogne, France under the name Mrs James or Madame James or Mrs Johnson, intending for the move to be a short stay. She lived frugally but always paid her rent on time. Not having been summoned back to England, she moved to Versailles by the end of the year. Soon after, she moved to [[Saint-Cloud]], near Paris. It is suggested that she made these last two moved to be closer to her son Frederick, who was stationed in Paris as part of the British Army. While in France, she was defrauded by eldest daughter, Frances and son-in-law, Thomas Alsop after they accumulated large sums of debt in her name. During this time, both her mental and physical health was declining. Her health was worsening and she suffered from \u2018bilious attacks, pains in her side, swollen ankles, shortness of breath and increasing general weakness\u2019. She missed her children terribly and confessed in a letter that \u201cits is not, believe me, the feelings of pride, avarice, or the absence of those comforts I have all my life been accustomed to, that is killing me by inches; it is the loss of my only remaining comfort, the hope I used to live on from time to time, of seeing my children\u201d. She died alone and in poverty on 5 July 1816 from a ruptured blood vessel caused by violent inflammation of the chest and was buried in the town cemetery.<ref name=\"odnb\"/><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/mrsjordansprofes00toma|title=Mrs Jordan's profession : the story of a great actress and a future King|last=Tomalin, Claire, 1933-|date=1994|publisher=Viking|isbn=0670841595|location=London|oclc=31377468|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Mrs. Jordan's Profession: The Actress and the Prince'', [[Claire Tomalin]], 17 October 1994, Publisher: Viking, {{ISBN|0-670-84159-5}}\n*''Ladies of the Bedchamber'', Dennis Friedman, 2003, Publisher: Peter Owen, {{ISBN|0-7206-1244-6}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRGJhWpf2qcC&pg=PA177 The Delectable Dora Jordan], In Otis Skinner (1928) ''Mad Folk of the Theatre'' Publisher: Ayer Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0-8369-1851-9}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jordan, Dorothea}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1816 deaths]]\n[[Category:FitzClarence family|*]]\n[[Category:18th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:19th-century English women]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Irish people]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English courtesans]]\n[[Category:Irish courtesans]]\n[[Category:Mistresses of British royalty]]\n[[Category:People from County Waterford]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriates in France]]\n", "name_user": "Elmer Clark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTheatrical career:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorothea_Jordan"}
{"title_page": "B. R. Shetty", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty\n| image              = File:Dr BR Shetty Official Pic.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1942|08|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Udupi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] (now [[Karnataka]], India)\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = \n| known_for          = Founder and chairman, [[NMC Health]]\n| website            = {{url|brshetty.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty''' (born 1 August 1942) is an Indian-born [[billionaire]] businessman, and the founder of a number of companies based in the United Arab Emirates. He is founder of [[Abu Dhabi]]-based [[NMC Health]],<ref name=national/> and [[UAE Exchange]].<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\"/> He is also the founder and chairman of Neopharma, [[Finablr]] and BRS Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| title=I Want To Be The No. 1 Healthcare Provider in India Over The Next 10 Years| author=Paramita Chatterjee, Suman K Jha| date=23 March 2018| publisher=BusinessWorld| access-date=8 May 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012947/http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2018, the UAE Exchange brand became part of the financial services holding company, Finablr.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| title=Billionaire B.R. Shetty Launches New Financial Firms Holding Company Finablr| author=Mary Sophia| date=24 April 2018| publisher=Forbes Middle East| access-date=24 August 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073919/https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty's initial interest in 1975 was in hospitals and hospitality, and has since diversified into pharmaceuticals, financial services, retail, advertising and information technology.<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | title=Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424235811/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | archive-date=24 April 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref> He was included on the ''[[Forbes]]'' list of India's 100 Richest People in 2015 and was listed as the 42nd richest person in 2020.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| title=#47 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=14 April 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228013207/http://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| archive-date=28 December 2016|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| title=#42 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=20 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514112322/https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| archive-date=14 May 2019| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are allegations of misappropriation by Shetty at his companies and was forced to resign from his director positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/how-indian-billionaire-bavaguthu-raghuram-shetty-who-owned-2-floors-of-burj-khalifa-went-bust-2182896 | title=How Indian billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty went bust}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/440371-billionaire-br-shetty-resigns-from-abu-dhabis-nmc-health | title=Billionaire BR Shetty resigns from Abu Dhabi's NMC Health}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html | title=NMC into Administration}}</ref>\nDue to sharp drop in the share prices and Shetty pledging the shares for debts that he had incurred, it is believed that his net worth has fallen to fraction of the earlier estimate of $3.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/uae-based-br-shettys-fortune-drops-1-5bn-since-muddy-waters-attack/ | title=\"BR Shetty's fortune drops by $1.5 Billion| date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Consequently, Forbes has dropped Shetty from its 2020 annual list of billionaires.\n\nShetty fled the UAE fearing legal procedure there by lender banks, including Dubai Islamic Bank and ADCB.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/banking-finance/444829-nmc-health-goes-into-administration-after-succumbing-to-creditors|title=NMC Health goes into administration after succumbing to creditors|website=ArabianBusiness.com}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nShetty was born in [[Kapu, Karnataka|Kapu]], [[Udupi]] to [[Tulu language|Tulu]] speaking parents Shambhu Shetty and Koosamma Shetty in the 1940s to an ethnic [[Tuluva]] family.<ref name = \"Mangalorean Tuluva\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |title=Mangalorean Tuluva B R Shetty Buy's Travelex for 1 billion |date=14 June 2015 |accessdate=12 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802204342/http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty completed his pharmaceutical education in [[India]] and also served as the Vice-Chairman of the Municipal Council in Udupi. He married Chandrakumari Shetty and has four children.<ref name=\"Journey - Dr. B. R. Shetty\">{{cite web | url=http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | title=Journey \u2013 Dr. B. R. Shetty | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614205457/http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | archive-date=14 June 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShetty immigrated to the UAE in 1973. After working as the country's first medical representative,<ref name=national/> he founded [[NMC Health|New Medical Centre Health]] (NMC) in 1975 to fill the need for personalized, cost-effective healthcare accessible to all.<ref name=national/><ref name=namma>{{cite web| url=http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| title=Dr B.R.Shetty to build Abu Dhabi's first medical university in honour of Sheikh Zayed| date=24 June 2016| publisher=NamMa TV| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802174516/http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> At that time, his wife was the only doctor in the clinic.<ref name=emi/> NMC is now the largest private healthcare provider in the UAE with over four million patients annually across 45 facilities spread over 12 cities and 8 countries, including UAE, KSA, Oman, Spain, Italy, Denmark, Colombia and Brazil. It is the first healthcare company from the GCC and the first company from Abu Dhabi to be listed on the premium segment of the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is part of the coveted [[FTSE 100 Index]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|title=Gulf private hospitals group NMC eyes UK launch after leap into FTSE 100|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=2 September 2017|access-date=24 September 2017|first=Iain|last=Withers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913030605/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty established the [[UAE Exchange]] in 1980 in an attempt to ease the process of sending money by the expats to their families in their respective home countries. By 2016, it had expanded into over 31 countries and had approximately 800 direct offices. In 2014, it did over US$50 billion collectively in money remittance and exchange volumes.<ref name=emi>{{cite web| url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| title=Dubai Dreams: From jobless medical rep to billions - BR Shetty| author=VM Sathish| date=10 August 2016| publisher=Emirates 24/7| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606205018/http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty acquired [[Travelex]], a major foreign exchange company, in 2014.<ref name=national>{{cite web| url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| title=BR Shetty, the astute businessman who turned $8 into $1bn| author=Frank Kane| date=1 July 2014| publisher=The National| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428185222/http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| archive-date=28 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=khal/> Travelex has a global footprint including 1500 stores and 1300 ATMs across 27 countries.\n\nIn 2003, Shetty founded NMC Neopharma, a UAE based pharmaceutical manufacturer.<ref name=emi/> Inaugurated by the then President of India, [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] in Abu Dhabi, Neopharma is centered on using the concept of modular manufacturing following global benchmarks in manufacturing technology and putting in place efficient control mechanisms. Neopharma has a research and development wing and works to provide quality medicines at affordable prices. The company also contracts manufacturing for international pharmaceutical companies as well as generic brands for companies including, but not limited to, [[Merck Group|Merck]], [[Pfizer]], [[AstraZeneca]], and [[Boots UK]].<ref name=emi/>\n\nIn 2012, Shetty led NMC through an [[initial public offering|IPO]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]], which raised $330 million. The funds went towards building a specialty hospital in [[Khalifa City]], Abu Dhabi.<ref name=gulfnews>{{cite web| url=http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| title=Dr B.R. Shetty to expand his NMC group in UAE and GCC| author=Fareed Rahman| date=18 October 2014| publisher=Gulf News| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006162305/http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Shetty announced that he was building the first medical university in Abu Dhabi in honor of [[Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan|Sheikh Zayed]].<ref name=namma/> That same month, he was elected to be chairman of the Indian Business/Professional Group.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| title=BR Shetty wants to promote India-UAE ties through IBPG| date=7 June 2016| publisher=Bfirst| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925083522/http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| archive-date=25 September 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2016, Shetty announced that he was building a 400-bed super-specialty hospital in Udupi in Karnataka through B R S Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| title=Dr BR Shetty to Build 400-bed Super-specialty hospital in Udupi| date=25 August 2016| publisher=Mangalorean| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925132051/https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| archive-date=25 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty also owned a hospital in [[Alexandria]], two hospitals in Nepal, and acquired a hospital in Cairo as part of his personal portfolio under the same company.<ref name=gulfnews/>\n\nIn August 2019, BRS Ventures announced plans to invest $5 billion in developing healthcare facilities across India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | title=Old Jan Sangh hand, billionaire B R Shetty plans $5 billion investment in Indian healthcare | publisher=Business Today | accessdate=25 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825084836/https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | archive-date=25 August 2019 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Bloomberg News]] report casted doubts on his real holding amidst the short-selling of NMC Health by [[Muddy Waters Research]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/a-jet-setting-billionaire-had-it-all-then-carson-block-came-along/articleshow/74204580.cms|title=Jet-setting billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty had it all. Then Carson Block came along| publisher=Bloomberg| accessdate= 20 February 2020}}</ref> Also in February 2020, Shetty was ousted from the NMC Health board following a corporate governance scandal over his holdings in the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Ben Martin, Senior City|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nmcs-founder-forced-out-over-shares-scandal-cr59jz2s6|title=NMC's founder forced out over shares scandal|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html|title=NMC Heads to Administration After Giving In to Creditor Demands|website=finance.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nShetty has invested in a medical institution in the north Indian state of Uttarakhand. He is the founder and patron of the Indian Pharmaceutical Association in the Emirates, and is a member of the Advisory Board (Financial Sector), Economic Department, Government of Dubai, UAE and the Pharmaceutical Committee, Dubai. He is also the chairman of [[Abu Dhabi Indian School]] and Bright Riders School.<ref name=\"Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | title=Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815070908/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | archive-date=15 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|title=Chairman's Message {{!}} Bright Riders School, Abu Dhabi|website=brightriders.ae|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802164450/http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Shetty was elected as the Chairman to the board of directors of UAE Exchange.<ref name=khal>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|title=Dr B.R. Shetty takes over as chairman of UAE Exchange|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085905/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|title=UAE Exchange appoints B R Shetty as Chairman, Promoth Manghat as CEO|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=24 August 2015|publisher=Economic Times India|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424090633/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He was named chairman of The Indian Business/Professional Group in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|title=Dr B R Shetty to head The Indian Business/Professional Group|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085646/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> H. H. Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid al Maktoum nominated Shetty as a member of the UAE medical council in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bfirst.in/news/2016_09_09/12860|title=Businessman BR Shetty nominated to medical council by PM of Dubai|publisher=Bfirst}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Shetty announced that he would invest Rs 1000 crore ($157.3 million) to produce a film with director [[V. A. Shrikumar Menon]]. The film, starring [[Mohanlal]], was to be based on the novel [[Randamoozham]], a retelling of [[Mahabharata]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Billionaire B. R. Shetty aims for $1 billion in revenue from Indian film epic|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|access-date=28 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027181423/https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|archive-date=27 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\nIn May 2019, however, the film was shelved due to creative issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mohanlal's Rs 1000 crore film project 'Randamoozham' shelved|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|access-date=20 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805223955/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{{Overly detailed|Section|date=February 2020}}\nIn 2005, Shetty was awarded the highest civilian distinction in the Emirate, the [[Abu Dhabi Awards]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | title = Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty | date = 23 May 2015 | work = The National | access-date = 23 September 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190923071607/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | archive-date = 23 September 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Given by H. H. Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan]], the Crown Prince of Abu Dhabi, the first year the distinction was awarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|title=Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty|publisher=The National|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422235344/http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|archive-date=22 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2005, U.S. India Friendship Society presented Shetty the Distinguished Entrepreneur Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty received The Distinguished Entrepreneur Award from the US India Friendship Society|publisher=Neopharma|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173745/http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nShetty was honoured by the [[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]] in 2007.<ref name=\"The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman - Times of India\">{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/The-recipients-of-Pravasi-Bharatiya-Samman/articleshow/1113368.cms | title=The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman \u2013 Times of India | work=Times of India| accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees\">{{cite web | url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | title=New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees | publisher=Daijiworld Media Pvt Ltd Mangalore | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170744/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nErnst & Young Middle East honored Shetty with the Entrepreneur of the year finalist award in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|title=Five UAE execs in running for Ernst & Young award|publisher=Emirates 24/7|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085817/http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] awarded by the [[President of India]] in 2009 for his contribution in the field of trade and industry.<ref name=\"IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners - Khaleej Times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | title=IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners \u2013 Khaleej Times | work=Khaleej Times| accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808123305/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | archive-date=8 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, he received the Asian Achievers Award from the Human Achievers Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|title=Asian Achievers Awards for Dhahi Khalfan, others|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174100/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Pharma Leaders founded by Satya Brahma declared Shetty as Global Indian of the Year along with [[Kiran Mazumdar-Shaw|Kiran Mazumdar Shaw]] at 5th Annual Pharmaceutical Leadership Summit & Pharma Leaders Business Leadership Awards 2012 in Mumbai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|title=Biocon Chief Dr. Kiran Majumdar Shaw & NMC Chief Dr B.R.Shetty Declared Global Indian of the Year {{!}} Pharmaleaders TV|website=pharmaleaders.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024205347/http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|archive-date=24 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shetty was recognized as one of Asia's most promising leaders at the Asian Brand & Leadership Summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|title=UAE Exchange named leader, most promising brand in Asia|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085721/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In March 2013, he was awarded the International Achievers Summit's Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174516/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty received the Asian Business Leadership Forum India-UAE Business Icons Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|title=ABLF Awards 2013 Winners|publisher=ABLF|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211033716/http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|archive-date=11 December 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> He also received the 2013 Frost & Sullivan Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Frost & Sullivan - Lifetime Achievement Award for the Year 2013|publisher=Frost & Sullivan|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425031103/https://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|archive-date=25 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Forbes Middle East recognized Shetty with the Top Indian Leaders in the UAE Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/forbes-middle-east-unveils-top-indian-leaders-in-the-arab-region|title=Forbes Middle East Reveals Top Indian Leaders in the Arab World|website=Forbes Middle East|publisher=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also received the Lakshya Business Visionary Award in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|title=From salesman to biz tycoon: A serial entrepreneur's success mantras|publisher=Rediff|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173734/http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty was recognized with the International Achievement Award at the Indian Innovator Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|title=Indian Innovator Awards 2014|publisher=Entrepreneur Middle East|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173725/https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the Indian Club - Bahrain recognized Shetty with a Centenary Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|title=Bahrain : Dr Kalam presents Indian Club Centenary awards to Colaco, B R Shetty|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085429/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He received the Deal of the Year Award at the 2015 Indian CEO Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|title=Sunil Vaswani takes top honours at Indian CEO Awards|publisher=Arabian Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008135040/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|archive-date=8 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In June 2015, Shetty received the Business Personality of the Year award from Crowe Horwath International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty has received the prestigious Business Personality of the Year award|publisher=NMV Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805020024/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|archive-date=5 August 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> That same month, Shetty received the Arabian Indian Czars award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|title=Arabian Indian Czars Award: Times Now felicitates successful Indians in Middle East|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018060431/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|archive-date=18 October 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the Global Indian Achiever Award in 2015 from H. H. Sheikh Nahyan Bin Mubarak al Nahyan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Global Indian Achiever Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031042109/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|archive-date=31 October 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Also in 2015, H. H. Prince Faisal Bin Saud Bin Musaed Bin Abdulaziz presented Shetty with the National Cultural Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|title=Indian tycoon Shetty is honored with National Cultural Award|work=The Saudi Gazette|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173839/http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty's company, NMC Healthcare, received the Frost & Sullivan Middle East Integrated Healthcare Company of the Year Award in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|title=NMC guides the way for the UAE's healthcare sector|publisher=World Finance|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430214825/http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|archive-date=30 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, MILAAP honored Shetty with a Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174031/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2015 Gulf Business Industry Awards, Shetty was recognized as the Healthcare Business Leader of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|title=Gulf Business Industry Awards 2015: Business Leaders of the Year|date=9 September 2015|publisher=Gulf Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173736/http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In November 2015, he was felicitated by More Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|title=Dr. B.R.Setty Felicitated By Mor Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral, Dubai|publisher=Dr. B. R. Shetty|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424175818/http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Shetty's NMC Healthcare was recognized at the 6th Middle East Business Leaders Awards in 2015, where Shetty was given the Industry Excellence in Healthcare Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|title=Mebla honours industry leaders|work=khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085800/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Shetty received the Golden Peacock Lifetime Achievement Award for Business Leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|title=Roll of Honour|publisher=Golden Peacock Awards|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173821/http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2016, Shetty won the Business Excellence Award from the Indian Business & Professional Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty honoured with Business Excellence Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085934/http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Middlesex University in Dubai awarded Shetty an Honorary Doctorate in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|title=Middlesex Dubai Honorary Graduates|publisher=Middlesex University Dubai|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174731/http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Shetty was honored at the Annual Health Awards with a special award for his contribution to the region's healthcare industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|title=Dr. B. R. Shetty honoured at the Annual Health Awards 2017 (NMC Health plc)|publisher=World News|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085508/https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> The following month, Shetty received the Nadaprabhu Kempegowda International Award at the Kempegowda International Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|title=Kempegowda International Festival lays emphasis on uniting Okkaligas under roof|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174146/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Shetty was recognized by Forbes Middle East among the top Indian leaders in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|title=Revealed: Top Indian business leaders in Arab world|publisher=Gulf News Business|accessdate=25 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527090500/https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status = live}}</ref> In September 2018 Shetty received the C3 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=25 August 2019|title=C3 US-Arab Healthcare & Business Summit and Title Sponsor Alitheia Holdings Honors Keynote Speaker Dr. B.R. Shetty with Lifetime Achievement Award|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825020538/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|archive-date=25 August 2019|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brshetty.com/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shetty, B. R.}}\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Mangaloreans]]\n[[Category:Tulu people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi district]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Former billionaires]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty\n| image              = File:Dr BR Shetty Official Pic.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1942|08|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Udupi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] (now [[Karnataka]], India)\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = \n| known_for          = Founder and chairman, [[NMC Health]]\n| website            = {{url|brshetty.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty''' (born 1 August 1942) is an Indian-born [[billionaire]] businessman, and the founder of a number of companies based in the United Arab Emirates. He is founder and chairman of [[Abu Dhabi]]-based [[NMC Health]],<ref name=national/> and chairman of [[UAE Exchange]].<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\"/> He is also the founder and chairman of Neopharma, [[Finablr]] and BRS Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| title=I Want To Be The No. 1 Healthcare Provider in India Over The Next 10 Years| author=Paramita Chatterjee, Suman K Jha| date=23 March 2018| publisher=BusinessWorld| access-date=8 May 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012947/http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2018, the UAE Exchange brand became part of the financial services holding company, Finablr.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| title=Billionaire B.R. Shetty Launches New Financial Firms Holding Company Finablr| author=Mary Sophia| date=24 April 2018| publisher=Forbes Middle East| access-date=24 August 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073919/https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty's initial interest in 1975 was in hospitals and hospitality, and has since diversified into pharmaceuticals, financial services, retail, advertising and information technology.<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | title=Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424235811/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | archive-date=24 April 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref> He was included on the ''[[Forbes]]'' list of India's 100 Richest People in 2015 and was listed as the 42nd richest person in 2020.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| title=#47 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=14 April 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228013207/http://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| archive-date=28 December 2016|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| title=#42 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=20 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514112322/https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| archive-date=14 May 2019| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are allegations of misappropriation by Shetty at his companies and was forced to resign from his director positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/how-indian-billionaire-bavaguthu-raghuram-shetty-who-owned-2-floors-of-burj-khalifa-went-bust-2182896 | title=How Indian billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty went bust}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/440371-billionaire-br-shetty-resigns-from-abu-dhabis-nmc-health | title=Billionaire BR Shetty resigns from Abu Dhabi's NMC Health}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html | title=NMC into Administration}}</ref>\nDue to sharp drop in the share prices and Shetty pledging the shares for debts that he had incurred, it is believed that his net worth has fallen to fraction of the earlier estimate of $3.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/uae-based-br-shettys-fortune-drops-1-5bn-since-muddy-waters-attack/ | title=\"BR Shetty's fortune drops by $1.5 Billion| date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Consequently, Forbes has dropped Shetty from its 2020 annual list of billionaires.\n\nShetty fled the UAE fearing legal procedure there by lender banks, including Dubai Islamic Bank and ADCB.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/banking-finance/444829-nmc-health-goes-into-administration-after-succumbing-to-creditors|title=NMC Health goes into administration after succumbing to creditors|website=ArabianBusiness.com}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nShetty was born in [[Kapu, Karnataka|Kapu]], [[Udupi]] to [[Tulu language|Tulu]] speaking parents Shambhu Shetty and Koosamma Shetty in the 1940s to an ethnic [[Tuluva]] family.<ref name = \"Mangalorean Tuluva\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |title=Mangalorean Tuluva B R Shetty Buy's Travelex for 1 billion |date=14 June 2015 |accessdate=12 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802204342/http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty completed his pharmaceutical education in [[India]] and also served as the Vice-Chairman of the Municipal Council in Udupi. He married Chandrakumari Shetty and has four children.<ref name=\"Journey - Dr. B. R. Shetty\">{{cite web | url=http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | title=Journey \u2013 Dr. B. R. Shetty | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614205457/http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | archive-date=14 June 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShetty immigrated to the UAE in 1973. After working as the country's first medical representative,<ref name=national/> he founded [[NMC Health|New Medical Centre Health]] (NMC) in 1975 to fill the need for personalized, cost-effective healthcare accessible to all.<ref name=national/><ref name=namma>{{cite web| url=http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| title=Dr B.R.Shetty to build Abu Dhabi's first medical university in honour of Sheikh Zayed| date=24 June 2016| publisher=NamMa TV| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802174516/http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> At that time, his wife was the only doctor in the clinic.<ref name=emi/> NMC is now the largest private healthcare provider in the UAE with over four million patients annually across 45 facilities spread over 12 cities and 8 countries, including UAE, KSA, Oman, Spain, Italy, Denmark, Colombia and Brazil. It is the first healthcare company from the GCC and the first company from Abu Dhabi to be listed on the premium segment of the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is part of the coveted [[FTSE 100 Index]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|title=Gulf private hospitals group NMC eyes UK launch after leap into FTSE 100|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=2 September 2017|access-date=24 September 2017|first=Iain|last=Withers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913030605/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty established the [[UAE Exchange]] in 1980 in an attempt to ease the process of sending money by the expats to their families in their respective home countries. By 2016, it had expanded into over 31 countries and had approximately 800 direct offices. In 2014, it did over US$50 billion collectively in money remittance and exchange volumes.<ref name=emi>{{cite web| url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| title=Dubai Dreams: From jobless medical rep to billions - BR Shetty| author=VM Sathish| date=10 August 2016| publisher=Emirates 24/7| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606205018/http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty acquired [[Travelex]], a major foreign exchange company, in 2014.<ref name=national>{{cite web| url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| title=BR Shetty, the astute businessman who turned $8 into $1bn| author=Frank Kane| date=1 July 2014| publisher=The National| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428185222/http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| archive-date=28 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=khal/> Travelex has a global footprint including 1500 stores and 1300 ATMs across 27 countries.\n\nIn 2003, Shetty founded NMC Neopharma, a UAE based pharmaceutical manufacturer.<ref name=emi/> Inaugurated by the then President of India, [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] in Abu Dhabi, Neopharma is centered on using the concept of modular manufacturing following global benchmarks in manufacturing technology and putting in place efficient control mechanisms. Neopharma has a research and development wing and works to provide quality medicines at affordable prices. The company also contracts manufacturing for international pharmaceutical companies as well as generic brands for companies including, but not limited to, [[Merck Group|Merck]], [[Pfizer]], [[AstraZeneca]], and [[Boots UK]].<ref name=emi/>\n\nIn 2012, Shetty led NMC through an [[initial public offering|IPO]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]], which raised $330 million. The funds went towards building a specialty hospital in [[Khalifa City]], Abu Dhabi.<ref name=gulfnews>{{cite web| url=http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| title=Dr B.R. Shetty to expand his NMC group in UAE and GCC| author=Fareed Rahman| date=18 October 2014| publisher=Gulf News| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006162305/http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Shetty announced that he was building the first medical university in Abu Dhabi in honor of [[Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan|Sheikh Zayed]].<ref name=namma/> That same month, he was elected to be chairman of the Indian Business/Professional Group.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| title=BR Shetty wants to promote India-UAE ties through IBPG| date=7 June 2016| publisher=Bfirst| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925083522/http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| archive-date=25 September 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2016, Shetty announced that he was building a 400-bed super-specialty hospital in Udupi in Karnataka through B R S Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| title=Dr BR Shetty to Build 400-bed Super-specialty hospital in Udupi| date=25 August 2016| publisher=Mangalorean| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925132051/https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| archive-date=25 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty also owned a hospital in [[Alexandria]], two hospitals in Nepal, and acquired a hospital in Cairo as part of his personal portfolio under the same company.<ref name=gulfnews/>\n\nIn August 2019, BRS Ventures announced plans to invest $5 billion in developing healthcare facilities across India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | title=Old Jan Sangh hand, billionaire B R Shetty plans $5 billion investment in Indian healthcare | publisher=Business Today | accessdate=25 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825084836/https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | archive-date=25 August 2019 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Bloomberg News]] report casted doubts on his real holding amidst the short-selling of NMC Health by [[Muddy Waters Research]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/a-jet-setting-billionaire-had-it-all-then-carson-block-came-along/articleshow/74204580.cms|title=Jet-setting billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty had it all. Then Carson Block came along| publisher=Bloomberg| accessdate= 20 February 2020}}</ref> Also in February 2020, Shetty was ousted from the NMC Health board following a corporate governance scandal over his holdings in the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Ben Martin, Senior City|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nmcs-founder-forced-out-over-shares-scandal-cr59jz2s6|title=NMC's founder forced out over shares scandal|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html|title=NMC Heads to Administration After Giving In to Creditor Demands|website=finance.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nShetty has invested in a medical institution in the north Indian state of Uttarakhand. He is the founder and patron of the Indian Pharmaceutical Association in the Emirates, and is a member of the Advisory Board (Financial Sector), Economic Department, Government of Dubai, UAE and the Pharmaceutical Committee, Dubai. He is also the chairman of [[Abu Dhabi Indian School]] and Bright Riders School.<ref name=\"Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | title=Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815070908/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | archive-date=15 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|title=Chairman's Message {{!}} Bright Riders School, Abu Dhabi|website=brightriders.ae|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802164450/http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Shetty was elected as the Chairman to the board of directors of UAE Exchange.<ref name=khal>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|title=Dr B.R. Shetty takes over as chairman of UAE Exchange|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085905/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|title=UAE Exchange appoints B R Shetty as Chairman, Promoth Manghat as CEO|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=24 August 2015|publisher=Economic Times India|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424090633/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He was named chairman of The Indian Business/Professional Group in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|title=Dr B R Shetty to head The Indian Business/Professional Group|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085646/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> H. H. Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid al Maktoum nominated Shetty as a member of the UAE medical council in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bfirst.in/news/2016_09_09/12860|title=Businessman BR Shetty nominated to medical council by PM of Dubai|publisher=Bfirst}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Shetty announced that he would invest Rs 1000 crore ($157.3 million) to produce a film with director [[V. A. Shrikumar Menon]]. The film, starring [[Mohanlal]], was to be based on the novel [[Randamoozham]], a retelling of [[Mahabharata]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Billionaire B. R. Shetty aims for $1 billion in revenue from Indian film epic|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|access-date=28 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027181423/https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|archive-date=27 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\nIn May 2019, however, the film was shelved due to creative issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mohanlal's Rs 1000 crore film project 'Randamoozham' shelved|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|access-date=20 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805223955/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{{Overly detailed|Section|date=February 2020}}\nIn 2005, Shetty was awarded the highest civilian distinction in the Emirate, the [[Abu Dhabi Awards]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | title = Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty | date = 23 May 2015 | work = The National | access-date = 23 September 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190923071607/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | archive-date = 23 September 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Given by H. H. Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan]], the Crown Prince of Abu Dhabi, the first year the distinction was awarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|title=Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty|publisher=The National|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422235344/http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|archive-date=22 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2005, U.S. India Friendship Society presented Shetty the Distinguished Entrepreneur Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty received The Distinguished Entrepreneur Award from the US India Friendship Society|publisher=Neopharma|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173745/http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nShetty was honoured by the [[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]] in 2007.<ref name=\"The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman - Times of India\">{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/The-recipients-of-Pravasi-Bharatiya-Samman/articleshow/1113368.cms | title=The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman \u2013 Times of India | work=Times of India| accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees\">{{cite web | url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | title=New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees | publisher=Daijiworld Media Pvt Ltd Mangalore | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170744/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nErnst & Young Middle East honored Shetty with the Entrepreneur of the year finalist award in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|title=Five UAE execs in running for Ernst & Young award|publisher=Emirates 24/7|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085817/http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] awarded by the [[President of India]] in 2009 for his contribution in the field of trade and industry.<ref name=\"IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners - Khaleej Times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | title=IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners \u2013 Khaleej Times | work=Khaleej Times| accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808123305/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | archive-date=8 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, he received the Asian Achievers Award from the Human Achievers Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|title=Asian Achievers Awards for Dhahi Khalfan, others|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174100/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Pharma Leaders founded by Satya Brahma declared Shetty as Global Indian of the Year along with [[Kiran Mazumdar-Shaw|Kiran Mazumdar Shaw]] at 5th Annual Pharmaceutical Leadership Summit & Pharma Leaders Business Leadership Awards 2012 in Mumbai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|title=Biocon Chief Dr. Kiran Majumdar Shaw & NMC Chief Dr B.R.Shetty Declared Global Indian of the Year {{!}} Pharmaleaders TV|website=pharmaleaders.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024205347/http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|archive-date=24 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shetty was recognized as one of Asia's most promising leaders at the Asian Brand & Leadership Summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|title=UAE Exchange named leader, most promising brand in Asia|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085721/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In March 2013, he was awarded the International Achievers Summit's Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174516/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty received the Asian Business Leadership Forum India-UAE Business Icons Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|title=ABLF Awards 2013 Winners|publisher=ABLF|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211033716/http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|archive-date=11 December 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> He also received the 2013 Frost & Sullivan Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Frost & Sullivan - Lifetime Achievement Award for the Year 2013|publisher=Frost & Sullivan|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425031103/https://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|archive-date=25 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Forbes Middle East recognized Shetty with the Top Indian Leaders in the UAE Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/forbes-middle-east-unveils-top-indian-leaders-in-the-arab-region|title=Forbes Middle East Reveals Top Indian Leaders in the Arab World|website=Forbes Middle East|publisher=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also received the Lakshya Business Visionary Award in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|title=From salesman to biz tycoon: A serial entrepreneur's success mantras|publisher=Rediff|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173734/http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty was recognized with the International Achievement Award at the Indian Innovator Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|title=Indian Innovator Awards 2014|publisher=Entrepreneur Middle East|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173725/https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the Indian Club - Bahrain recognized Shetty with a Centenary Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|title=Bahrain : Dr Kalam presents Indian Club Centenary awards to Colaco, B R Shetty|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085429/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He received the Deal of the Year Award at the 2015 Indian CEO Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|title=Sunil Vaswani takes top honours at Indian CEO Awards|publisher=Arabian Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008135040/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|archive-date=8 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In June 2015, Shetty received the Business Personality of the Year award from Crowe Horwath International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty has received the prestigious Business Personality of the Year award|publisher=NMV Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805020024/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|archive-date=5 August 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> That same month, Shetty received the Arabian Indian Czars award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|title=Arabian Indian Czars Award: Times Now felicitates successful Indians in Middle East|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018060431/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|archive-date=18 October 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the Global Indian Achiever Award in 2015 from H. H. Sheikh Nahyan Bin Mubarak al Nahyan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Global Indian Achiever Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031042109/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|archive-date=31 October 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Also in 2015, H. H. Prince Faisal Bin Saud Bin Musaed Bin Abdulaziz presented Shetty with the National Cultural Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|title=Indian tycoon Shetty is honored with National Cultural Award|work=The Saudi Gazette|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173839/http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty's company, NMC Healthcare, received the Frost & Sullivan Middle East Integrated Healthcare Company of the Year Award in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|title=NMC guides the way for the UAE's healthcare sector|publisher=World Finance|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430214825/http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|archive-date=30 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, MILAAP honored Shetty with a Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174031/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2015 Gulf Business Industry Awards, Shetty was recognized as the Healthcare Business Leader of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|title=Gulf Business Industry Awards 2015: Business Leaders of the Year|date=9 September 2015|publisher=Gulf Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173736/http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In November 2015, he was felicitated by More Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|title=Dr. B.R.Setty Felicitated By Mor Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral, Dubai|publisher=Dr. B. R. Shetty|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424175818/http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Shetty's NMC Healthcare was recognized at the 6th Middle East Business Leaders Awards in 2015, where Shetty was given the Industry Excellence in Healthcare Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|title=Mebla honours industry leaders|work=khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085800/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Shetty received the Golden Peacock Lifetime Achievement Award for Business Leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|title=Roll of Honour|publisher=Golden Peacock Awards|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173821/http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2016, Shetty won the Business Excellence Award from the Indian Business & Professional Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty honoured with Business Excellence Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085934/http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Middlesex University in Dubai awarded Shetty an Honorary Doctorate in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|title=Middlesex Dubai Honorary Graduates|publisher=Middlesex University Dubai|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174731/http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Shetty was honored at the Annual Health Awards with a special award for his contribution to the region's healthcare industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|title=Dr. B. R. Shetty honoured at the Annual Health Awards 2017 (NMC Health plc)|publisher=World News|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085508/https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> The following month, Shetty received the Nadaprabhu Kempegowda International Award at the Kempegowda International Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|title=Kempegowda International Festival lays emphasis on uniting Okkaligas under roof|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174146/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Shetty was recognized by Forbes Middle East among the top Indian leaders in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|title=Revealed: Top Indian business leaders in Arab world|publisher=Gulf News Business|accessdate=25 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527090500/https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status = live}}</ref> In September 2018 Shetty received the C3 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=25 August 2019|title=C3 US-Arab Healthcare & Business Summit and Title Sponsor Alitheia Holdings Honors Keynote Speaker Dr. B.R. Shetty with Lifetime Achievement Award|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825020538/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|archive-date=25 August 2019|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brshetty.com/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shetty, B. R.}}\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Mangaloreans]]\n[[Category:Tulu people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi district]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Former billionaires]]\n", "name_user": "CharlestonMaani", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed references to \"Chairman\" as Shetty has stepped down.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B._R._Shetty"}
{"title_page": "Captain Tom Moore", "text_new": "{{short description|British fundraiser|bot = PearBOT 5}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Captain Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom_Moore_walking_intiative.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = Tom Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30}}\n| birth_place        = Keighley, Yorkshire, United Kindgdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British\n| alma_mater         = Keighley Grammar School, West Yorkshire\n| occupation         = Ex-Army captain\n| years_active       = 2020 - present\n| known_for          = Fund raising for National Health Service (United Kingdom) during the COVID-19 pandemic year of 2020\n| notable_works      = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| website            = {{URL|https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|tomswalkforthenhs}}\n}}\n'''Captain Tom Moore''' (b. April, 1920) is a 99 year old British [[Fundraising|fund-raise]]<nowiki/>r and an ex-army [[veteran]] who embarked on a walking initiative to complete 100 laps of his garden in [[Bedfordshire]] on Monday, 6 April 2020 to raise funds for the [[National Health Service]], [[United Kingdom]] to aid the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] pandemic. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a31.4m for 'humbled' NHS|date=2020-04-14|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/14/war-hero-99-raises-1500000-nhs-walking-100-lengths-garden-12553898/|title=War hero, 99, raises \u00a32,000,000 for the NHS by walking 100 lengths of his garden|date=2020-04-14|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== The fund raising walk ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|306x306px|Caption Tom Moore in the fund-raising initiative walk. April 2020.]]\nWalking with the aid of a [[Walker (mobility)|frame]], Captain Moore aimed to walk 100 laps of the 25-metre (82ft) loop in his 50 metre long garden in [[Marston Moreteyne|Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] in 10-lap chunks, before his 100th birthday on 30 April 2020 to raise money for the NHS. Moore began raising funds with an initial target of one thousand pounds to thank the healthcare workers of NHS who continue to work hard throughout the corona-virus [[pandemic]] and who earlier in his life helped him with the treatment for cancer and a broken hip.\n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 pound goal was realised on Friday 10 April hence the target was subsequently increased to \u00a3100,000 and then to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world got involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html|title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019|date=2020-04-14|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media got light of the endeavour and as of Tuesday 14 April, Captain Moore\u2019s [[JustGiving]] page has raised an excess of \u00a34 million for NHS Charities Together. Moore who has recently taken to twitter has expressed joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.\n\nFunds raised by Moore is being spent on well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCaptain Moore is currently doing 10 laps a day of his back garden in order to achieve his initial aim of 100 laps, he has now said he will not stop and aims to do another 100 laps.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* \"When you think of who it is all for - all those brave and super doctors and nurses we have got - I think they deserve every penny and I hope we get some more for them, too.\"\n* \"We have had problems before - we have overcome them - and we shall all overcome the same thing again.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> ([[BBC News]])- Captain Tom Moore.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Biography ==\nCaptain Moore was born and raised in Keighley, West Yorkshire, United Kingdom and attended the Keighley Grammar School as a child and later went on to complete an apprenticeship as a [[Civil engineer|Civil Engineer]]. He enlisted in 8 [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment|Duke of Wellington]] (145 [[Royal Armoured Corps]]) at the beginning of World War II, and in 1940 was selected for Officer Training. After completion he rose to the rank of [[Captain]] and was posted in the 9 DWR in [[India]] and served and fought in India, [[Arakan]] and [[Myanmar|Burma]]. After completion of his duties abroad Moore returned to United Kingdom and became an Instructor at [[Armoured fighting vehicle|The Armoured Fighting Vehicle School]] in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]]. In 2007 he moved to Marston Moretaine, Bedfordshire with his daughter, son-in-law and two grandchildren.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS|website=JustGiving|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n[https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Captain Tom Moore's fund-raising page.]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:Fundraising events]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n<br />\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British fundraiser|bot = PearBOT 5}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Captain Tom Moore\n| image              = Tom_Moore_walking_intiative.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| other_names        = \n| birth_name         = Tom Moore\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1920|4|30}}\n| birth_place        = Keighley, Yorkshire, United Kindgdom\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = British\n| alma_mater         = Keighley Grammar School, West Yorkshire\n| occupation         = Ex-Army captain\n| years_active       = 2020 - present\n| known_for          = Fund raising for National Health Service (United Kingdom) during the COVID-19 pandemic year of 2020\n| notable_works      = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| website            = https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs\n}}\n'''Captain Tom Moore''' (b. April, 1920) is a 99 year old British [[Fundraising|fund-raise]]<nowiki/>r and an ex-army [[veteran]] who embarked on a walking initiative to complete 100 laps of his garden in [[Bedfordshire]] on Monday, 6 April 2020 to raise funds for the [[National Health Service]], [[United Kingdom]] to aid the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] pandemic. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52278746|title=Army veteran, 99, raises \u00a31.4m for 'humbled' NHS|date=2020-04-14|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/14/war-hero-99-raises-1500000-nhs-walking-100-lengths-garden-12553898/|title=War hero, 99, raises \u00a32,000,000 for the NHS by walking 100 lengths of his garden|date=2020-04-14|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== The fund raising walk ==\n[[File:Captain Tom Moore fundraising walk.jpg|thumb|306x306px|Caption Tom Moore in the fund-raising initiative walk. April 2020.]]\nWalking with the aid of a [[Walker (mobility)|frame]], Captain Moore aimed to walk 100 laps of the 25-metre (82ft) loop in his 50 metre long garden in [[Marston Moreteyne|Marston Moretaine]], [[Bedfordshire]] in 10-lap chunks, before his 100th birthday on 30 April 2020 to raise money for the NHS. Moore began raising funds with an initial target of one thousand pounds to thank the healthcare workers of NHS who continue to work hard throughout the corona-virus [[pandemic]] and who earlier in his life helped him with the treatment for cancer and a broken hip.\n\nThe initial \u00a31,000 pound goal was realised on Friday 10 April hence the target was subsequently increased to \u00a3100,000 and then to \u00a3500,000 as more people around the world got involved.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/nhs-100-birthday-walk-army-veteran-tom-moore-fundraise-a9463561.html|title=99-year-old army veteran raises more than \u00a31m for NHS with \u2018100th birthday walk\u2019|date=2020-04-14|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe fund-raising soared exponentially when the British media got light of the endeavour and as of Tuesday 14 April, Captain Moore\u2019s [[JustGiving]] page has raised an excess of \u00a34 million for NHS Charities Together. Moore who has recently taken to twitter has expressed joy over accumulating such a staggering amount of money for the NHS.\n\nFunds raised by Moore is being spent on well-being packs for National Health Service staff facilitating rest and recuperation rooms, devices to enable hospital patients to keep in contact with family members, and community groups who support patients once discharged from hospitals.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nCaptain Moore is currently doing 10 laps a day of his back garden in order to achieve his initial aim of 100 laps, he has now said he will not stop and aims to do another 100 laps.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* \"When you think of who it is all for - all those brave and super doctors and nurses we have got - I think they deserve every penny and I hope we get some more for them, too.\"\n* \"We have had problems before - we have overcome them - and we shall all overcome the same thing again.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> ([[BBC News]])- Captain Tom Moore.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Biography ==\nCaptain Moore was born and raised in Keighley, West Yorkshire, United Kingdom and attended the Keighley Grammar School as a child and later went on to complete an apprenticeship as a [[Civil engineer|Civil Engineer]]. He enlisted in 8 [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment|Duke of Wellington]] (145 [[Royal Armoured Corps]]) at the beginning of World War II, and in 1940 was selected for Officer Training. After completion he rose to the rank of [[Captain]] and was posted in the 9 DWR in [[India]] and served and fought in India, [[Arakan]] and [[Myanmar|Burma]]. After completion of his duties abroad Moore returned to United Kingdom and became an Instructor at [[Armoured fighting vehicle|The Armoured Fighting Vehicle School]] in [[Bovington Camp|Bovington]]. In 2007 he moved to Marston Moretaine, Bedfordshire with his daughter, son-in-law and two grandchildren.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs|title=Captain Tom Moore's 100th Birthday Walk for the NHS|website=JustGiving|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n[https://www.justgiving.com/fundraising/tomswalkforthenhs Captain Tom Moore's fund-raising page.]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Tom}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:Fundraising events]]\n[[Category:Charity events in the United Kingdom]]\n<br />\n", "name_user": "Tabletop123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captain_Tom_Moore"}
{"title_page": "Pat O'Neill (filmmaker)", "text_new": "[[File:Pat O'Neill.jpg|thumb|Pat O'Neill (right) in 2012.]]\n'''Patrick O'Neill''' (born 1939 in [[Los Angeles, California]]) is an American independent experimental filmmaker and artist who has also worked in the special effects industry. Although his work embraces an extremely wide technical and aesthetic scope, he is perhaps best known for his startling, surrealistic, and humorous film compositions achieved through a mastery of the [[optical printer]].  His films and other artworks often reveal a complex and mysterious interest in the connections and clashes between the natural world and human civilization.  O'Neill has also produced a prodigious body of work in drawing, collage, sculpture, installation, and many other media.\n\nHis early 16mm films include ''Runs Good'' (1970), ''Easyout'' (1971), and ''Down Wind'' (1973). His later 35mm films include ''[[Water and Power]]'' (1989), ''Trouble in the Image'' (1996), and ''The Decay of Fiction'' (2002). On December 30, 2008, ''Water and Power'' was added to the [[National Film Registry]].<ref>{{cite news \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = New titles in U.S. National Film Registry\n  | work = [[The Globe and Mail]]\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = [[Associated Press]]\n  | date = December 30, 2008\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081230.wfilmlist1230/BNStory/Entertainment\n  | accessdate = 2008-12-30}}</ref>\nPrints of O'Neill's films are held in numerous archives and museums around the world, and his complete collection resides at the [[Academy Film Archive|Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences Film Archive]], where several of his short works have been preserved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pat O'Neill Collection|url=http://www.oscars.org/film-archive/collections/pat-oneill-collection|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>  In 2009, ''Water and Power'' was preserved by the Academy in collaboration with O'Neill.\n\nHe has also taught at the [[California Institute of the Arts]]. He influenced a generation of CalArts students, who include [[Adam Beckett]], Robert Blalack, Chris Casady, and [[Larry Cuba]], who all later went on to work on the special effects of the original [[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]].\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''By the Sea'' (with [[Robert Abel (animator)|Robert Abel]]) (1963)\n* ''Bump City'' (1964)\n* ''7362'' (1965\u201367)\n* ''Coming Down'' (aka ''Heresy'') (1968) (promo film for [[The United States of America (band)|The United States of America]])\n* ''Screen'' (1969)\n* ''Runs Good'' (1970)\n* ''Easyout'' (1972)\n* ''The Last of the Persimmons'' (1972)\n* ''Down Wind'' (1973)\n* ''Saugus Series'' (1974)\n* ''Sidewinder's Delta'' (1976)\n* ''Foregrounds'' (1978)\n* ''Sleeping Dogs (Never Lie)'' (1978)\n* ''Two Sweeps'' (1979)\n* ''Let's Make a Sandwich'' (1978\u201382)\n* ''[[Water and Power]]'' (1989)\n* ''Trouble in the Image'' (1996)\n* ''Coreopsis'' (1998)\n* ''Squirtgun Step Print'' (1998)\n* ''[[The Decay of Fiction]]'' (2002)\n* ''Horizontal Boundaries'' (2008)\n* ''I Put Out my Hands'' (2009)\n* ''I Open the Window'' (2009)\n* ''Starting to go Bad'' (2009)\n* ''Painter & Ball 4-14'' (2010)\n* ''Ojo Caliente'' (2012)\n* ''Where the Chocolate Mountains'' (2015)<ref>[https://www.redcat.org/event/pat-o-neill-where-chocolate-mountains REDCAT]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n*''Pat O'Neill: Views From Lookout Mountain'' by Paul Arthur, Howard Singerman, Erika Suderburg, and Julie Lazar ed.Steidl/Santa Monica Museum of Art, 2004\n*''Pat O'Neill: Another Kind of Record''. Los Angeles: The Ice Plant, 2008\n*\"An Interview with Pat O'Neill\" David James. '''Millennium Film Journal'' No 30/31 Fall 1997.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lookoutmountainstudios.com/ Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0642271|name=Pat O'Neill}}\n* [http://canyoncinema.com/catalog/filmmaker/?i=231 Canyon Cinema]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091130011904/http://www.rosamundfelsen.com/oneill/index.php]\n* [https://www.academia.edu/3069773/The_Decay_of_Fiction/ Review of Decay of Fiction]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oneill, Pat}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:American experimental filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Pat O'Neill.jpg|thumb|Pat O'Neill (right) on 2012.]]\n'''Patrick O'Neill''' (born 1939 in [[Los Angeles, California]]) is an American independent experimental filmmaker and artist who has also worked in the special effects industry. Although his work embraces an extremely wide technical and aesthetic scope, he is perhaps best known for his startling, surrealistic, and humorous film compositions achieved through a mastery of the [[optical printer]].  His films and other artworks often reveal a complex and mysterious interest in the connections and clashes between the natural world and human civilization.  O'Neill has also produced a prodigious body of work in drawing, collage, sculpture, installation, and many other media.\n\nHis early 16mm films include ''Runs Good'' (1970), ''Easyout'' (1971), and ''Down Wind'' (1973). His later 35mm films include ''[[Water and Power]]'' (1989), ''Trouble in the Image'' (1996), and ''The Decay of Fiction'' (2002). On December 30, 2008, ''Water and Power'' was added to the [[National Film Registry]].<ref>{{cite news \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = New titles in U.S. National Film Registry\n  | work = [[The Globe and Mail]]\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = [[Associated Press]]\n  | date = December 30, 2008\n  | url = https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20081230.wfilmlist1230/BNStory/Entertainment\n  | accessdate = 2008-12-30}}</ref>\nPrints of O'Neill's films are held in numerous archives and museums around the world, and his complete collection resides at the [[Academy Film Archive|Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences Film Archive]], where several of his short works have been preserved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pat O'Neill Collection|url=http://www.oscars.org/film-archive/collections/pat-oneill-collection|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>  In 2009, ''Water and Power'' was preserved by the Academy in collaboration with O'Neill.\n\nHe has also taught at the [[California Institute of the Arts]]. He influenced a generation of CalArts students, who include [[Adam Beckett]], Robert Blalack, Chris Casady, and [[Larry Cuba]], who all later went on to work on the special effects of the original [[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]].\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''By the Sea'' (with [[Robert Abel (animator)|Robert Abel]]) (1963)\n* ''Bump City'' (1964)\n* ''7362'' (1965\u201367)\n* ''Coming Down'' (aka ''Heresy'') (1968) (promo film for [[The United States of America (band)|The United States of America]])\n* ''Screen'' (1969)\n* ''Runs Good'' (1970)\n* ''Easyout'' (1972)\n* ''The Last of the Persimmons'' (1972)\n* ''Down Wind'' (1973)\n* ''Saugus Series'' (1974)\n* ''Sidewinder's Delta'' (1976)\n* ''Foregrounds'' (1978)\n* ''Sleeping Dogs (Never Lie)'' (1978)\n* ''Two Sweeps'' (1979)\n* ''Let's Make a Sandwich'' (1978\u201382)\n* ''[[Water and Power]]'' (1989)\n* ''Trouble in the Image'' (1996)\n* ''Coreopsis'' (1998)\n* ''Squirtgun Step Print'' (1998)\n* ''[[The Decay of Fiction]]'' (2002)\n* ''Horizontal Boundaries'' (2008)\n* ''I Put Out my Hands'' (2009)\n* ''I Open the Window'' (2009)\n* ''Starting to go Bad'' (2009)\n* ''Painter & Ball 4-14'' (2010)\n* ''Ojo Caliente'' (2012)\n* ''Where the Chocolate Mountains'' (2015)<ref>[https://www.redcat.org/event/pat-o-neill-where-chocolate-mountains REDCAT]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n*''Pat O'Neill: Views From Lookout Mountain'' by Paul Arthur, Howard Singerman, Erika Suderburg, and Julie Lazar ed.Steidl/Santa Monica Museum of Art, 2004\n*''Pat O'Neill